{"title_page": "Nadba", "text_new": "The '''Nadba''' ({{lang-ar|\u0627\u0644\u0646\u062f\u0628\u0647}})  is a cultural ceremonial [[battle cry]] native to the [[Shihuh]], an Arab tribe that inhabits [[Musandam Peninsula|Ruus Al Jibal (Musandam Peninsula)]] in [[eastern Arabia]]. Its is a famous cultural dance in the [[United Arab Emirates]], particularly in [[Ras Al Khaimah]].<ref name=AB>{{cite web|url=https://www.albayan.ae/five-senses/2010-08-17-1.274624|title=\u0627\u0644\u0646\u062f\u0628\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0634\u062d\u064a\u0629 \u0646\u062f\u0627\u0621 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0641\u0631\u0627\u062d \u0648\u0627\u064a\u0642\u0648\u0646\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0627\u0646\u062a\u0635\u0627\u0631|newspaper=albayan|date=17 August 2010}}</ref> Although a battle cry, its use is not restricted during time of combat but today is commonly performed in ceremonies, weddings, feasts, and to honor guests. It is performed by a group of tribesmen, who usually pick a leader (called the Nadeeb - {{lang-ar|\u0627\u0644\u0646\u062f\u064a\u0628}}) to lead the battle cry. The battle cry is performed by the leader raising his left arm across his chest to his mouth and his right arm bent above and behind his head, then straightening and bending the raised hand as the he howls in an ascending and descending scale in Arabic to the lyrics of \"Al Shehhi Al Mayhob\" while the surrounding tribesmen, who form a circle around the leader (called Kabkub - {{lang-ar|\u0643\u0628\u0643\u0648\u0628}}), chant to the lyrics of \"Ho..Ho..Ho\" (shortened word of [[Allah]]u). The members performing the ceremony are call Ridida ({{lang-ar|\u0627\u0644\u0631\u062f\u064a\u062f\u0629}}).<ref name=B>{{cite book|first=B.|last=Thomas|title=Travels in Oman. Visit of B. Thomas to the Musandam Peninsula. 1928. Notes on Shihuh dialects & people, also Kumzaris' [\u200e10r]|publisher=British Library: India Office Records and Private Papers|date=March 1927|url=https://www.qdl.qa/en/archive/81055/vdc_100055148454.0x000022|pages=33\u201336}}</ref><ref name=AB />\n\n==See also==\n*[[Culture of the United Arab Emirates]]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=B8iC6rSjZVY Video of the Nadba on YouTube]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n", "text_old": "The '''Nadba''' ({{lang-ar|\u0627\u0644\u0646\u062f\u0628\u0647}})  is a cultural ceremonial [[battle cry]] native to the [[Shihuh]], an Arab tribe that inhabits [[Musandam Peninsula|Ruus Al Jibal (Musandam Peninsula)]] in [[eastern Arabia]]. Its is a famous cultural dance in the [[United Arab Emirates]], particularly in [[Ras Al Khaimah]].<ref name=AB>{{cite web|url=https://www.albayan.ae/five-senses/2010-08-17-1.274624|title=\u0627\u0644\u0646\u062f\u0628\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0634\u062d\u064a\u0629 \u0646\u062f\u0627\u0621 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0641\u0631\u0627\u062d \u0648\u0627\u064a\u0642\u0648\u0646\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0627\u0646\u062a\u0635\u0627\u0631|newspaper=albayan|date=17 August 2010}}</ref> Although a battle cry, its use is not restricted during time of combat but today is commonly performed in ceremonies, weddings, feasts, and to honor guests. It is performed by a group of tribesmen, who usually pick a leader (called the Nadeeb - {{lang-ar|\u0627\u0644\u0646\u062f\u064a\u0628}}) to lead the battle cry. The battle cry is performed by the leader raising his left arm across his chest to his mouth and his right arm bent above and behind his head, then straightening and bending the raised hand as the he howls in an ascending and descending scale in Arabic to the lyrics of \"Al Shehhi Al Mayhob\" while the surrounding tribesmen, who form a circle around the leader (called Kabkub - {{lang-ar|\u0643\u0628\u0643\u0648\u0628}}), chant to the lyrics of \"Ho..Ho..Ho\" (shortened word of [[Allah|Allahu]]). The members performing the ceremony are call Ridida ({{lang-ar|\u0627\u0644\u0631\u062f\u064a\u062f\u0629}}).<ref name=B>{{cite book|first=B.|last=Thomas|title=Travels in Oman. Visit of B. Thomas to the Musandam Peninsula. 1928. Notes on Shihuh dialects & people, also Kumzaris' [\u200e10r]|publisher=British Library: India Office Records and Private Papers|date=March 1927|url=https://www.qdl.qa/en/archive/81055/vdc_100055148454.0x000022|page=33-36}}</ref><ref name=AB></ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Culture of the United Arab Emirates]]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=B8iC6rSjZVY Video of the Nadba on YouTube]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up, addeduncategorisedtag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nadba"}
{"title_page": "Dwight Heine", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Dwight Heine\n| image = Dwight Heine.png\n\n| office1 = [[List of colonial governors of the Marshall Islands|District Administrator of the Marshall Islands]]\n| term1 = 1965\u20131969\n| predecessor1 = [[Peter Tali Coleman]]\n| successor1 = [[Robert D. Law (administrator)|Robert D. Law]]\n\n| office2 = Speaker of the [[Congress of the Trust Territory of the Pacific Islands|TTPI House of Representatives]]\n| term2 = 1965\n| successor2 = [[Bethwel Henry]]\n\n| office3 = Member of the [[Congress of the Trust Territory of the Pacific Islands|TTPI House of Representatives]]\n| term3 = 1965\n| successor3 = [[Ekpap Silk]]\n| constituency3 = Marshalls 6th District\n\n| birth_date = 12 October 1919<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=iaVBsBMDbUcC&lpg=PA138&ots=ytmpbUMFq_&pg=PA138#v=onepage&q&f=false ''The Department of State Bulletin, Volume 31, Part 1''], p138</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Ebon Atoll]], [[South Seas Mandate]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1984|11|13|1919|10|12|df=y}}<ref name=HA>\"Dwight Heine, Micronesian leader, dies at 65\" ''The Honolulu Advertiser, 17 November 1984</ref> \n| death_place = [[Marshall Islands]]\n}}\n\n'''Dwight Heine''' (12 October 1919 \u2013 13 November 1984) was a [[Marshall Islands|Marshallese]] politician. He was both a member and speaker of the [[Legislature of the Marshall Islands|Marshall Islands Congress]], Congress of Micronesia and the [[Congress of the Trust Territory of the Pacific Islands|House of Representatives]] of the Trust Territory of the Pacific Islands, before serving as District Administrator of the Marshall Islands from 1965 to 1969.\n\n==Biography==\nHeine was born in October 1919 on [[Ebon Atoll]], the grandson of an Australian vicar.<ref name=JT>Jack A. Tobin (2002) ''[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=yUSHbrkbYSwC&lpg=PA374&pg=PA374#v=onepage&q&f=false Stories from the Marshall Islands: Bwebwenato J\u0101n Ael\u014dn\u0304 Kein]'' p374</ref> He attended Protestant schools in Ebon and [[Kosrae]].<ref name=JT/> During [[World War II]] his parents were executed by the Japanese.<ref name=HA/>\n\nAfter the war, he became the first Micronesian to graduate from an American college, studying at the [[University of Hawaii]] between 1948 and 1950 and again from 1957 to 1959, and earning a BA in 1959.<ref name=HA/><ref name=JT/><ref name=MR1/> After a brief stint teaching at the [[Bailey Olter High School|Pacific Islands Central School]], he became a superintendent of primary schools in the Marshall Islands, as well as president of the Marshall Islands Import Export Company.<ref name=MR1/> In 1952 he was awarded a United Nations fellowship to study administration.<ref name=MR1>[http://www.pacificdigitallibrary.org/cgi-bin/pdl?e=q-000off-pdl--00-2--0--010-TE--4-------0-1l--10en-50---20-text-%22dwight+heine%22--00-3-1-00bySR-0-0-000utfZz-8-00&a=d&c=pdl&srp=0&srn=0&cl=search&d=HASH1ff266d19ae20826474252.5 Heine begins work on U.N. Fellowship] ''Micronesian Monthly'', November 1952</ref> He later became District Educational Administrator for the Marshalls.<ref>[http://www.pacificdigitallibrary.org/cgi-bin/pdl?e=q-000off-pdl--00-2--0--010-TE--4-------0-1l--10en-50---20-text-%22dwight+heine%22--00-3-1-00bySR-0-0-000utfZz-8-00&a=d&c=pdl&srp=0&srn=0&cl=search&d=HASHb733ef8031bae3799be0d1.9 \"Station WSZO Broadcasting\"] ''Micronesian Reporter, May\u2013June 1959</ref> In the 1950s he appeared at the [[United Nations]] to protest atomic bomb tests at [[Bikini Atoll]],<ref name=PIM/> after which he was temporarily removed from his position in the civil service.<ref name=HA/> He was elected to the [[Legislature of the Marshall Islands|Marshall Islands Congress]], serving as its president.\n\nIn 1961 he became a member of the new Congress of Micronesia, and was its first Speaker. When the body was converted to the [[Congress of the Trust Territory of the Pacific Islands]] in January 1965, he contested the first [[1965 Trust Territory of the Pacific Islands parliamentary election|elections]] to the lower house, the General Assembly (later renamed the House of Representatives), and was elected from the Marshalls 6th District. Following the elections, he was elected Speaker of the Assembly. However, in October 1965 he was appointed District Administrator of the Marshall Islands, resigning his seat in Congress.<ref name=TT>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=EHX2SMi0hRQC&pg=PA198&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiN3dGw-LPnAhXkpHEKHScGDhEQ6AEIQjAD#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Trust Territory of the Pacific Islands''] Office of United Nations Political Affairs, pp198</ref>\n\nHe served as District Administrator until 1969, after which he became special consultant to the [[High Commissioner of the Trust Territory of the Pacific Islands|High Commissioner]], a position he held until he retired in 1980.<ref name=JT/><ref name=HA/> He died in the Marshall Islands in November 1984 at the age of 63.<ref name=PIM>[https://nla.gov.au/nla.obj-334941320/view?partId=nla.obj-335091237#page/n64/mode/1up Dwight Heine] ''Pacific Islands Monthly'', January 1985, p65</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Heine, Dwight}}\n[[Category:1919 births]]\n[[Category:University of Hawaii alumni]]\n[[Category:Marshallese educators]]\n[[Category:Marshallese civil servants]]\n[[Category:Members of the Legislature of the Marshall Islands]]\n[[Category:Speakers of the Legislature of the Marshall Islands]]\n[[Category:Members of the Congress of the Trust Territory of the Pacific Islands]]\n[[Category:District Administrators of the Marshall Islands]]\n[[Category:1984 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Dwight Heine\n| image = Dwight Heine.png\n\n| office1 = [[List of colonial governors of the Marshall Islands|District Administrator of the Marshall Islands]]\n| term1 = 1965\u20131969\n| predecessor1 = [[Peter Tali Coleman]]\n| successor1 = [[Robert D. Law (administrator)|Robert D. Law]]\n\n| office2 = Speaker of the [[Congress of the Trust Territory of the Pacific Islands|TTPI House of Representatives]]\n| term2 = 1965\n| successor2 = [[Bethwel Henry]]\n\n| office3 = Member of the [[Congress of the Trust Territory of the Pacific Islands|TTPI House of Representatives]]\n| term3 = 1965\n| successor3 = [[Ekpap Silk]]\n| constituency3 = Marshalls 6th District\n\n| birth_date = 12 October 1919<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=iaVBsBMDbUcC&lpg=PA138&ots=ytmpbUMFq_&pg=PA138#v=onepage&q&f=false ''The Department of State Bulletin, Volume 31, Part 1''], p138</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Ebon Atoll]], [[South Seas Mandate]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1984|11|13|1919|10|12|df=y}}<ref name=HA>\"Dwight Heine, Micronesian leader, dies at 65\" ''The Honolulu Advertiser, 17 November 1984</ref> \n| death_place = [[Marshall Islands]]\n}}\n\n'''Dwight Heine''' (12 October 1919 \u2013 13 November 1984) was a [[Marshall Islands|Marshallese]] politician. He was both a member and speaker of the [[Legislature of the Marshall Islands|Marshall Islands Congress]], Congress of Micronesia and the [[Congress of the Trust Territory of the Pacific Islands|House of Representatives]] of the Trust Territory of the Pacific Islands, before serving as District Administrator of the Marshall Islands from 1965 to 1969.\n\n==Biography==\nHeine was born in October 1919 on [[Ebon Atoll]], the grandson of an Australian vicar.<ref name=JT>Jack A. Tobin (2002) ''[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=yUSHbrkbYSwC&lpg=PA374&pg=PA374#v=onepage&q&f=false Stories from the Marshall Islands: Bwebwenato J\u0101n Ael\u014dn\u0304 Kein]'' p374</ref> He attended Protestant schools in Ebon and [[Kosrae]].<ref name=JT/> During [[World War II]] his parents were executed by the Japanese.<ref name=HA/>\n\nAfter the war, he became the first Micronesian to graduate from an American college, studying at the [[University of Hawaii]] between 1948 to 1950 and again from 1957 to 1959, and earning a BA in 1959.<ref name=HA/><ref name=JT/><ref name=MR1/> After a brief stint teaching at the [[Bailey Olter High School|Pacific Islands Central School]], he became a superintendent of primary schools in the Marshall Islands, as well as president of the Marshall Islands Import Export Company.<ref name=MR1/> In 1952 he was awarded a United Nations fellowship to study administration.<ref name=MR1>[http://www.pacificdigitallibrary.org/cgi-bin/pdl?e=q-000off-pdl--00-2--0--010-TE--4-------0-1l--10en-50---20-text-%22dwight+heine%22--00-3-1-00bySR-0-0-000utfZz-8-00&a=d&c=pdl&srp=0&srn=0&cl=search&d=HASH1ff266d19ae20826474252.5 Heine begins work on U.N. Fellowship] ''Micronesian Monthly'', November 1952</ref> He later became District Educational Administrator for the Marshalls.<ref>[http://www.pacificdigitallibrary.org/cgi-bin/pdl?e=q-000off-pdl--00-2--0--010-TE--4-------0-1l--10en-50---20-text-%22dwight+heine%22--00-3-1-00bySR-0-0-000utfZz-8-00&a=d&c=pdl&srp=0&srn=0&cl=search&d=HASHb733ef8031bae3799be0d1.9 \"Station WSZO Broadcasting\"] ''Micronesian Reporter, May\u2013June 1959</ref> In the 1950s he appeared at the [[United Nations]] to protest atomic bomb tests at [[Bikini Atoll]],<ref name=PIM/> after which he was temporarily removed from his position in the civil service.<ref name=HA/> He was elected to the [[Legislature of the Marshall Islands|Marshall Islands Congress]], serving as its president.\n\nIn 1961 he became a member of the new Congress of Micronesia, and was its first Speaker. When the body was converted to the [[Congress of the Trust Territory of the Pacific Islands]] in January 1965, he contested the first [[1965 Trust Territory of the Pacific Islands parliamentary election|elections]] to the the lower house, the General Assembly (later renamed the House of Representatives), and was elected from the Marshalls 6th District. Following the elections, he was elected Speaker of the Assembly. However, in October 1965 he was appointed District Administrator of the Marshall Islands, resigning his seat in Congress.<ref name=TT>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=EHX2SMi0hRQC&pg=PA198&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiN3dGw-LPnAhXkpHEKHScGDhEQ6AEIQjAD#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Trust Territory of the Pacific Islands''] Office of United Nations Political Affairs, pp198</ref>\n\nHe served as District Administrator until 1969, after which he became special consultant to the [[High Commissioner of the Trust Territory of the Pacific Islands|High Commissioner]], a position he held until he retired in 1980.<ref name=JT/><ref name=HA/> He died in the Marshall Islands in November 1984 at the age of 63.<ref name=PIM>[https://nla.gov.au/nla.obj-334941320/view?partId=nla.obj-335091237#page/n64/mode/1up Dwight Heine] ''Pacific Islands Monthly'', January 1985, p65</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Heine, Dwight}}\n[[Category:1919 births]]\n[[Category:University of Hawaii alumni]]\n[[Category:Marshallese educators]]\n[[Category:Marshallese civil servants]]\n[[Category:Members of the Legislature of the Marshall Islands]]\n[[Category:Speakers of the Legislature of the Marshall Islands]]\n[[Category:Members of the Congress of the Trust Territory of the Pacific Islands]]\n[[Category:District Administrators of the Marshall Islands]]\n[[Category:1984 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBiography:clean up,typo(s) fixed: between 1948 to \u2192 between 1948 and, the the \u2192 the", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dwight_Heine"}
{"title_page": "The Muppets' Wizard of Oz", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name = The Muppets'<br />Wizard of Oz\n| image = Woz-poster001sm.png\n| image_alt = \n| caption = Official poster\n| genre = <!--Must be sourced per Template:Infobox television instructions-->\n| based_on = ''[[The Wonderful Wizard of Oz]]'' by [[L. Frank Baum]]\n| writer = {{plainlist|\n* Debra Frank\n* Steve L. Hayes\n* Quentin Tarantino\n* [[Tom Martin (writer)|Tom Martin]]\n* [[Adam F. Goldberg]]\n}}\n| story = {{Plainlist|\n* Debra Frank\n* Steve L. Hayes\n}}\n| director = [[Kirk Thatcher]]\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Ashanti (singer)|Ashanti]]\n* [[Jeffrey Tambor]]\n* [[Quentin Tarantino]]\n* [[David Alan Grier]]\n* [[Queen Latifah]]\n* [[Steve Whitmire]]\n* [[Dave Goelz]]\n* [[Bill Barretta]]\n* [[Eric Jacobson]]\n}}\n| theme_music_composer = [[Michael Giacchino]]\n| country = {{Plainlist|\n* United States\n* Canada\n}}\n| language = English\n| producer = [[Bill Barretta]]\n| editor = Gregg Featherman\n| cinematography = Tony Westman\n| runtime = {{Plainlist|\n* 72 minutes\n* 100 minutes (Extended Edition)\n}}\n| company = {{Plainlist|\n* [[The Jim Henson Company]]\n* [[The Muppets Holding Company]]\n* [[ABC Studios|Touchstone Television]]\n* [[Fox 21 Television Studios|Fox Television Studios]]\n}}\n| distributor = [[Buena Vista Television]]\n| network = [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]\n| first_aired = {{Film date|2005|04|27|[[Tribeca Film Festival|Tribeca]]|2005|05|20|TV=y}}\n}}\n'''''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz''''' is a 2005 [[fantasy]] [[television film]] directed by [[Kirk Thatcher]] and starring [[Ashanti (singer)|Ashanti]] and [[The Muppets]] with supporting roles done by [[Jeffrey Tambor]], [[Quentin Tarantino]], [[David Alan Grier]], and [[Queen Latifah]]. The film was produced by [[Bill Barretta]] and written by Debra Frank, Steve L. Hayes, [[Tom Martin (writer)|Tom Martin]], and [[Adam F. Goldberg]] based on a story by Frank and Hayes.\n\nA modernized adaptation of [[L. Frank Baum]]'s 1900 novel, ''[[The Wonderful Wizard of Oz]]'', the story follows young [[Dorothy Gale]], who works in her Aunt Em's diner, but dreams of becoming a singer somewhere beyond her small Kansas town. Swept up by a tornado, in her [[trailer home]] with pet prawn Toto, she lands in Oz and embarks on a journey to meet the Wizard who can help make her dreams come true.\n\nThe film was co-produced by [[The Muppets Studio]], [[ABC Studios|Touchstone Television]], and [[Fox 21 Television Studios|Fox Television Studios]], in association with [[The Jim Henson Company]]. Right after Disney bought the rights to The Muppets in 2004, pre-production on ''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz'' took place throughout February 2004, and [[Principal photography|filming]] occurred during September 2004. ABC made several changes to the film after the initial script was written, ultimately deciding to adapt plot elements from Baum's original novel rather than the 1939 [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] musical film, ''[[The Wizard of Oz (1939 film)|The Wizard of Oz]]''. As with the preceding [[The Muppets|Muppet]] films, ''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz'' became a musical, and included five new songs written and composed by [[Michael Giacchino]]. The special is the first Muppets special without the involvement of veteran performer [[Jerry Nelson]] following his 2004 retirement from physical performing. His characters of [[List of Muppets#Lew Zealand|Lew Zealand]] and [[Dr. Teeth and the Electric Mayhem#Sgt. Floyd Pepper|Floyd Pepper]], were respectively performed by [[Bill Barretta]] and [[John Kennedy (puppeteer)|John Kennedy]]. Barretta also debuts as the new permanent performer of [[Dr. Teeth and The Electric Mayhem#Dr. Teeth|Dr. Teeth]] due to Kennedy now performing Floyd. The production also marked the feature film debut of [[Eric Jacobson]] as the performer of [[Sam Eagle]], a character originally performed by [[Frank Oz]].\n\n''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz'' premiered on April 27, 2005 at the [[Tribeca Film Festival]]. The film's television premiere was broadcast on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] on May 20, 2005, as the final ''[[ABC Movie of the Week]]''. The film received generally mixed to negative reviews from critics, who felt that the film was too mature for young audiences and that the cameo scenes and popular culture references were unnecessary.\n\n==Plot==\n{{plot|date=September 2018}}\n[[Dorothy Gale]] ([[Ashanti (singer)|Ashanti]]) is an orphaned teenage girl living in a trailer park in [[Kansas]]. Her [[Aunt Em]] ([[Queen Latifah]]) and [[Uncle Henry (Oz)|Uncle Henry]] ([[David Alan Grier]]) own a diner, to which Dorothy works for [[room and board]]. Her dream of becoming a singer is slim, but when waiting on some [[Truck driver|trucker]]s Dorothy overhears that the Muppets are conducting a cross-country show called \"Star Hunt\" and are looking for a backup singer. Aunt Em disapproves, but with Uncle Henry's best wishes, she goes to the audition. However, the Muppets are about to end the audition, and Dorothy only manages to give them a demo CD that she created beforehand. In returning home, the [[civil defense siren]]s sound as a [[tornado]] is headed for Dorothy's trailer park. When Aunt Em and Uncle Henry run into the county storm shelter for safety, Dorothy hurries back to her family's mobile home to get [[Toto (Oz)|Toto]], her pet [[prawn]]. She does not make it out in time, and the two are swept by the tornado across the vast fields of Kansas. When Dorothy climbs out of the wreckage, she finds that Toto ([[Pep\u00e9 the King Prawn]]) can talk and that she is no longer in Kansas.\n\nDorothy and Toto discover that they are in [[Munchkin Country|Munchkinland]], a small town part of the vast [[Land of Oz]]. After discussing her situation with the town's people, the Munchkins (played by [[Rizzo the Rat]] and the other rats), she learns that the land's ruler the [[Wizard of Oz (character)|Wizard]], has the power to grant her wish of becoming a famous singer. She meets the [[Good Witch of the North]] ([[Miss Piggy]]), and receives a pair of magic [[Silver Shoes|silver slippers]] from the [[Wicked Witch of the East]] (Miss Piggy), the Witch of the North's sister who was killed when Dorothy's trailer fell on her. Soon after, she embarks on a journey with Toto on the [[yellow brick road]] to meet the Wizard of Oz, who lives in the [[Emerald City]], the capital of Oz. On her journey, she meets three creatures: a [[Scarecrow (Oz)|Scarecrow]] ([[Kermit the Frog|Kermit]]), a [[Tin Woodman|Tin Thing]] ([[Gonzo (Muppet)|Gonzo]]), and a [[Cowardly Lion]] ([[Fozzie Bear|Fozzie]]). They are also seeking the Wizard of Oz to give them a brain, heart, and courage, respectively. The group meets various obstacles involving a deep gorge where the Kalidah Critics ([[Statler and Waldorf]]) are heckling them and a Poppy Field Club run by [[List of Muppets#Clifford|Clifford]] which nearly puts them to sleep. After arriving at the Emerald City and meeting the Wizard, Dorothy and her friends are sent to retrieve the [[Wicked Witch of the West]]'s magic eye, a tool she uses to see anything she desires in the Land of Oz.\n\nThe group assumes that completing this task will result in the granting of their wishes. The Wicked Witch of the West (Miss Piggy) sees them coming and consults with her pet [[List of Muppets#Additional characters|Foo-Foo]] and her henchman [[List of Muppets#Johnny Fiama and Sal Minella|Johnny Fiama]]. When the Wicked Witch of the West plans to have either her pack of 40 great man-eating wolves, a flock of 40 [[American crow|crow]]s of despair, a swarm of angry black bees, a group of vicious squirrels, or a group of bloodthirsty cockatoos to do away with them, Johnny tells her that the animals that work for her are unavailable due to various reasons. This forces her to resort to using her Magic Biker Cap to call Sal Minella and the other [[Winged monkeys|Flying Monkeys]] (played by [[List of Muppets#Sweetums|Sweetums]], [[List of Muppets#Crazy Harry|Crazy Harry]], Black Dog, Bobo the Bear, Calico, Old Tom, Spotted Dick, and Aretha from ''[[Fraggle Rock]]'') to deal with them. The Witch and the Flying Monkeys capture Dorothy, Toto and Lion while Scarecrow and Tin Thing are dismantled by the Flying Monkeys.\n\nAfter being threatened to be killed by her, Toto calls the Munchkins, who set him and Dorothy free and hold up the witch. During the final battle, it cuts away to a scene where [[Quentin Tarantino]] is having a meeting with Kermit, discussing ideas for how Dorothy can defeat the Wicked Witch of the West. Tarantino's ideas are deemed too expensive and too violent for a Muppet movie, so they agree for Dorothy to do a powerful kick on the witch. Cutting back to the action, Dorothy kicks the witch into her own \"bottled water bath\" which contains tap water (to which she is severely allergic). Angel Marie admitted that he filled the water bottles with tap water to restock them. This action causes the Wicked Witch of the West to melt as Johnny averts Foo-Foo's eyes. With the Wicked Witch of the West dead, Dorothy finds the magic eye floating in the tub unharmed and grabs it.\n\nDorothy gains control of the Flying Monkeys by giving back the group's Magic Biker Cap to Sal Minella. She has Scarecrow and Tin Thing rebuilt by the Flying Monkeys. Then she and her friends travel back to the Emerald City to have their wishes granted. When they all storm into the Wizard's room, they discover it is merely a Hollywood effects stage and that the Wizard ([[Jeffrey Tambor]]) is just an ordinary man, pretending. He asked for the witch's eye so that she could not see him for who he really was. Even so, he still proceeds to grant their wishes. Dorothy finally becomes a singer in the Land of Oz, but she realizes that all she ever really wanted was to go back home and be with her family. After traveling back to Munchkinland, she meets [[Glinda the Good Witch|Glinda the Good Witch of the South]] (Miss Piggy), who tells her that if she clicks her heels together three times, she will be able to go anywhere she desires, contrary to how the Good Witch of the North said to get to the Emerald City. She does so, saying \"take me home to Aunt Em\".\n\nShe is then spun by the slippers' charm into Kansas, and, much to her surprise, she finds out that Kermit was looking for her, saying that she had the best voice they heard on the whole search, and that she has been chosen to go on the Star Hunt. Dorothy, having been reunited with her aunt and uncle, and feeling that she is not ready to leave Kansas to become a real star, rejects, but Aunt Em says that she wants her to go with the Muppets on their Star Hunt, much to her even bigger surprise. She then sings \"Good Life\" on television with them at the Muppet Theater as the film ends.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Ashanti (singer)|Ashanti]] as [[Dorothy Gale]]: A [[Kansas]] teen dreaming of leaving her home and becoming a singer.\n* [[Queen Latifah]] as [[Aunt Em]]: Dorothy's aunt and co-owner of the family diner in Kansas.\n* [[David Alan Grier]] as [[Uncle Henry (Oz)|Uncle Henry]]: Dorothy's uncle and co-owner of the family diner.\n* [[Jeffrey Tambor]] as The [[Wizard of Oz (character)|Wizard of Oz]]: The legendary Wizard of Oz. This is Tambor's second appearance in a ''Muppet'' film, the first being ''[[Muppets from Space]]''.\n* [[Quentin Tarantino]] as Himself ''([[#Distribution|Extended version]])'': In a short appearance with [[Kermit the Frog]], Tarantino discusses violent ideas on how to stop the [[Wicked Witch of the West]]. Despite the fact that his role is minor, his name is still mentioned in the movie trailer and listed on the cover of both the Video and DVD.\n* [[Kelly Osbourne]] as [[Dorothy Gale]] (post-makeover) ''([[#Distribution|Extended version]])'': Appears in a brief cameo as Dorothy when she first comes out of the ''Magic Makeover Machine'' in [[Emerald City]].\n\n===Muppet performers===\n{{main|List of Muppets}}\n\n* [[Steve Whitmire]] as:\n** [[Kermit the Frog]] as Himself/[[Scarecrow (Oz)|Scarecrow]]: A scarecrow in search of a brain. Scarecrow is constantly mocked by the crows in Oz, as he is defenseless and cannot do anything to stop them. Prior to Dorothy's journey, Kermit organizes a talent scout for a star for a new show. After Dorothy's return, he hires her.\n** [[Beaker (Muppet)|Beaker]]: He appears as an Emerald City Technician. Beaker also appears at the end in the Muppets' show.\n** [[Rizzo the Rat]] as Himself/Mayor of Munchkinland. He occasionally aids Dorothy when she is in danger. Prior to Dorothy's journey, Rizzo is seen assisting [[Bean Bunny]] in loading equipment into the Muppets' bus. He returns for the Muppets' show at the end of the film.\n** [[Statler and Waldorf|Statler]] as Kalidah Critic #1. He heckles Dorothy and her friends as they try to cross a log.\n* [[Dave Goelz]] as:\n** [[Gonzo (Muppet)|The Great Gonzo]] as the Himself/[[Tin Woodman|Tin Thing]]: A robot in search of a heart. Originally human, the Tin Thing was turned into a robot by the Wicked Witch of the West who was angry at him for asking to leave her palace and marry his [[Engagement|fianc\u00e9e]], [[Camilla the Chicken]]. He also appears at the end of the film in the Muppets' show.\n** [[Bunsen Honeydew|Dr. Bunsen Honeydew]]: He appears as an Emerald City Technician. He also appears at the end of the film in the Muppets' show.\n** [[Statler and Waldorf|Waldorf]] as Kalidah Critic #2. He and the other Kalidah Critic heckles Dorothy and her friends as they try to cross a log.\n** [[Dr. Teeth and The Electric Mayhem#Zoot|Zoot]]: He performs backup for the songs \"Naptime\", and for \"The Witch is in the House\", and appears at the end of the film in the Muppets' new show.\n* [[Bill Barretta]] as:\n** [[Pep\u00e9 the King Prawn]] as [[Toto (Oz)|Toto]]: Dorothy's pet prawn and first companion on her journey. In Kansas, Toto was a prawn that lived in a fish bowl in Dorothy's room. Strangely, Pep\u00e9 doesn't appear in the finale with the other Muppets.\n** [[Dr. Teeth and The Electric Mayhem#Dr. Teeth|Dr. Teeth]]: He performs \"Naptime\", and also performs in \"The Witch is in the House\". He appears again at the end of the film in the Muppets' show.\n** [[List of Muppets#Johnny Fiama and Sal Minella|Johnny Fiama]]: He appears as one of the henchmen of the Wicked Witch of the West, and is supposedly her love interest. \n** [[List of Muppets#Bobo the Bear|Bobo the Bear]]: He appears as one of the henchmen of the Wicked Witch of the West.\n** [[List of Muppets#Lew Zealand|Lew Zealand]]: He briefly appears in Emerald City at the red carpet event, asking Dorothy to sign his boomerang fish. \n** [[Swedish Chef|The Swedish Chef]]: He provides the [[Bran Flakes]] for the Wizard. \n** Bubba the Rat: He assists the Mayor of Munchkin Land in getting Dorothy and the Lion out of Poppyfields.\n* [[Eric Jacobson]] as:\n** [[Miss Piggy]] as Herself: She appears early on with Kermit, and tries to get rid of Dorothy. She returns at the end of the film for the Muppets' show.\n*** as The [[Wicked Witch of the West]]: The Wicked Witch that terrifies all that meet her.\n*** as The [[Good Witch of the North|Tattypoo the Good Witch of the North]]: The Good Witch that gives Dorothy the silver slippers.\n*** as The [[Glinda the Good Witch|Glinda the Good Witch of the South]]: The other Good Witch that shows Dorothy how to get home.\n*** as The [[Wicked Witch of the East]]: The original owner of the magic slippers who was killed by Dorothy's falling mobile home.\n** [[Fozzie Bear]] as Himself/[[Cowardly Lion|Cowardly Bear]]: A nervous and frightened lion stand-up comic that accompanies Dorothy and the others on their journey. Fozzie shows up at the end of the film in the Muppets' show.\n** [[Animal (Muppet)|Animal]]: He performs in the songs \"Naptime\" and \"The Witch is in the House\".\n** [[Sam Eagle]]: He appears as the Guardian of the Gates. Sam doesn't appear in the Muppets' show at the end of the film.\n* [[Brian Henson]] as:\n** Sal Manilla as Sal, a [[Winged monkeys|Flying Monkey]]: He accompanies Johnny for much of the film.\n* [[Kevin Clash]] as:\n** [[List of Muppets#Clifford|Clifford]]: He appears as the manager of the Poppy Field Club. \n** Mulch: He appears briefly in Poppyfields.\n** Black Dog as a [[Winged monkeys|Flying Monkey]]\n* [[John Kennedy (puppeteer)|John Kennedy]] as:\n** Angel Marie as a [[Winged monkeys|Flying Monkey]]: A servant of the Wicked Witch of the West.\n** [[Dr. Teeth and The Electric Mayhem#Sgt. Floyd Pepper|Floyd Pepper]]: He performs in \"Naptime\" and \"The Witch is in the House\".\n* Rickey Boyd as:\n** [[Scooter (Muppet)|Scooter]]: He appears as the Wizard's Assistant.\n** [[List of Muppets#Crazy Harry|Crazy Harry]] as a [[Winged monkeys|Flying Monkey]]\n* [[Tyler Bunch]] as:\n** [[Dr. Teeth and The Electric Mayhem#Janice|Janice]]: She performs in \"Naptime\" and \"The Witch is in the House\".\n** Old Tom as a [[Winged monkeys|Flying Monkey]]\n* [[Julianne Buescher]] as\n** Wizard's Green Lady and Chicken Forms\n* [[John Henson (puppeteer)|John Henson]] as\n** [[List of Muppets#Sweetums|Sweetums]] as a [[Winged monkeys|Flying Monkey]]: He provides the keys for the Cowardly Lion's escape from his cage.\n* [[Mike Quinn (puppeteer)|Mike Quinn]] as\n** Spotted Dick as a [[Winged monkeys|Flying Monkey]]\n* [[Allan Trautman]] as\n** [[American crow|Crow]]: He bothers the Scarecrow.\n** Old Tom as a [[Winged monkeys|Flying Monkey]]\n* [[Alice Dinnean]] as:\n** [[List of Muppets#Camilla the Chicken|Camilla the Chicken]]: The Tin Thing's girlfriend. The two are reunited later on in the film.\n** [[List of Muppets#Additional characters|Foo-Foo]]: Foo-Foo appears as the pet of the Wicked Witch of the West.\n\nWhitmire and Goelz make on-screen cameos as audience members at Aunt Em's Diner during the finale.\n===Background Muppets===\nRowlf the Dog, Bean Bunny, Zippity Zap, Zondra, Chip, Jowls, Clarissa, Pip and Pop, Treelo, Ojo, Tutter, Hillary the Owl, Cameraman, Bunnies, Penguins\n\n==Production==\nWhen [[The Walt Disney Company]] acquired the Muppets franchise from [[The Jim Henson Company]] in February 2004,<ref name=\"llc\">[http://www.henson.com/muppets.php \"''The Muppets'' at the Jim Henson Company.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080510143755/http://www.henson.com/muppets.php |date=2008-05-10 }} [[The Jim Henson Company]]. Retrieved: April 26, 2008.</ref><ref name=\"fozzie\">[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/3603954.stm \"Tarantino to star in Muppets film,\"] ''[[BBC News]]'', August 27, 2004, Retrieved: April 26, 2008.</ref> the Muppets were re-introduced to the public by marketing products and guest appearing on television shows such as ''[[Good Morning America]]'' and ''[[America's Funniest Home Videos]]''.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}} After a new film titled ''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz'' was announced by [[The Jim Henson Company]], [[Fox 21 Television Studios|Fox Television Studios]], [[Touchstone Television]], and the [[The Muppets Studio|Muppets Holding Company]] signed on to help produce it.<ref name=\"oz\">Gates, Anita. [https://www.nytimes.com/2005/05/20/arts/television/20mupp.html \"Muppets as Munchkins: We're Not in Kansas Anymore.\"] ''[[The New York Times]]'', May 20, 2005, p. E26. Retrieved: March 11, 2008.</ref>\n\nFilming took place throughout September 2004 in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]].<ref name=\"fozzie\"/> Before filming, ABC announced that the production would adapt elements from the original 1900 book, rather than [[The Wizard of Oz (1939 film)|the 1939 film]].<ref name=\"comp\">Adalian, Josef. [http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117901774.html?categoryid=1236&cs=1&query=muppets+oz \"The Muppets ready to take Oz.\"] ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', March 15, 2004. Retrieved: April 26, 2008.</ref> such as the [[Silver Shoes]] instead of the [[Ruby slippers]].  On August 25, 2004, it was announced that [[Hilary Duff]], [[Jessica Simpson]], and [[Ashanti (entertainer)|Ashanti]] had auditioned for the role of [[Dorothy Gale]], but Ashanti had won the part.<ref>Norment, Lynn. [http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1077/is_5_60/ai_n12934945 \"Ashanti: Answers critics & doubters.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120601021517/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1077/is_5_60/ai_n12934945/ |date=2012-06-01 }} ''[[Ebony (magazine)|Ebony]]'', March 2005. Retrieved: April 26, 2008.</ref><ref>[http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1490550/20040825/ashanti.jhtml \"For The Record: Quick News On Ashanti, Usher, Phil Spector, Taking Back Sunday, Kanye West, Jay-Z & More.\"] ''[[MTV]]'', August 25, 2004. Retrieved: April 26, 2008.</ref> When asked about how she felt about working with the Muppets, Ashanti replied, \"I love children, and to me, the Muppets are just like little kids.\"<ref name=\"gonzo\">Fonseca, Nicholas. [http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,1060837,00.html \"Wizard of Frog.\"] ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'', Issue 820, p. 66, May 20, 2005. Retrieved: April 26, 2008.</ref> She also stated, \"The director had to give me a few pointers and tips for acting with them, but the most important thing that I learned was to keep eye contact.\"<ref name=\"gonzo\"/> Also in August 2004, [[BBC News]] reported that [[Quentin Tarantino]] would appear in the film.<ref name=\"fozzie\"/>\n\n==Music==\n[[Michael Giacchino]], who had previously worked on a Muppet-related project which is video game ''[[Muppet Monster Adventure]]'' and would become an [[Academy Award]]-winning composer, worked with Jeannie Lurie, Adam Cohen, Debra Frank, and Steve Hayes to write five original songs for the film.<ref name=\"fozzie\"/><ref name=\"a\"/> The five songs created were \"Kansas\", \"When I'm With You\", \"It's a Good Life\", \"The Witch is in the House\", and \"Nap Time\". \"When I'm With You\" was later nominated for a [[Primetime Emmy]] in the Outstanding Music and Lyrics category,<ref name=\"emmy\">[http://www.emmys.tv/awards/2005pt/awards/music.php \"''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz'' nominated for Primetime Emmy.\"] [[Emmy Awards]]. Retrieved: March 27, 2008.</ref> but lost to \"Mary Jane/Mary Lane\" from ''[[Reefer Madness (2005 film)|Reefer Madness]]''.<ref name=\"emmy\"/> Ashanti and the Muppet cast, mainly Bill Barretta and Eric Jacobson, contributed the vocals for each of the songs.<ref name=\"a\"/> Ted Kryczko produced the album, Booker T. Washington White prepared the songs for recording, and Paul Silveira and Brandon Christy mixed the film's songs.<ref name=\"a\"/>\n\n===Soundtrack===\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Best of the Muppets featuring The Muppets' Wizard of Oz\n| type       = Soundtrack\n| artist     =\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = May 17, 2005\n| recorded   = [[Walt Disney Studios (Burbank)|Walt Disney Studios]]\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Pop rock]], [[soundtrack]]<ref name=\"ozcd\"/>\n| length     = 29:52<ref name=\"a\">''The Best of the Muppets featuring The Muppets' Wizard of Oz''. [[Walt Disney Records]], 2005.</ref>\n| label      = [[Walt Disney Records|Walt Disney]]\n| producer   = [[Sam Pottle]]\n| chronology = [[The Muppets]]\n| prev_title = [[The Muppet Show: Music, Mayhem, and More]]\n| prev_year  = 2002\n| next_title = [[The Muppets: A Green and Red Christmas]]\n| next_year  = 2006\n}}\n''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz'' official soundtrack was released on May 17, 2005.<ref name=\"ozcd\">[https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0009AJK98 \"''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz'' Soundtrack.\"] ''[[Amazon.com]]'', 2005. Retrieved: March 4, 2008.</ref> The album was an enhanced soundtrack titled ''Best of Muppets featuring The Muppets' Wizard of Oz'' as it was not a film-specific soundtrack, but an album featuring the Muppets' best songs from ''[[The Muppet Show]]'' as well as songs from the film.<ref name=\"ozcd\"/>\n\n'''Track listing'''<ref name=\"ozcd\"/>\n# \"''(Gotta Get Outta)''<ref>''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz DVD Film Intro, [[Closed Captioning]]''. ''[[Walt Disney Home Video]]'', 2005. Retrieved: April 26, 2008.</ref> Kansas\" - [[Ashanti (entertainer)|Ashanti]]\n# \"When I'm With You\" \u2013 [[Ashanti (entertainer)|Ashanti]], Kermit, Gonzo, Fozzie & Pepe\n# \"The Witch Is in the House\" \u2013 [[Miss Piggy]] with [[Dr. Teeth and The Electric Mayhem]]\n# \"Calling All Munchkins\" \u2013 The Munchkin Tap-Your-Knuckles Choir\n# \"Good Life\" \u2013 [[Ashanti (entertainer)|Ashanti]]\n# \"Nap Time\" \u2013 [[Dr. Teeth and The Electric Mayhem]]\n# \"[[The Muppet Show Theme]]\" \u2013 The Muppets\n# \"[[Mah N\u00e0 Mah N\u00e0]]\"\u2013 [[Mah N\u00e0 Mah N\u00e0|Mahna Mahna]] & the Two Snowths\n# \"[[Bein' Green]]\"\u2013 [[Kermit the Frog]]\n# \"[[Rainbow Connection]]\" \u2013 Kermit & Muppets With Sesame Street Gang \n# \"Lady of Spain\" \u2013 [[Marvin Suggs]] & his Muppaphone\n# \"[[Halfway Down the Stairs]]\"\u2013 Kermit & [[Robin the Frog|Robin]]\n# \"[[What Now My Love?]]\" \u2013 [[Miss Piggy]]\n# \"Tenderly\" \u2013 [[Dr. Teeth and The Electric Mayhem]]\n# \"Happy Feet\" \u2013 Kermit and the Frog Chorus\n\n==Release==\n''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz'' premiered on April 27, 2005 at the [[Tribeca Film Festival]].<ref>[http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news.aspx?id=20050329muppets01 \"''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz'' to premiere on April 27th, 2005 at the Tribeca Film Festival.\"] ''The Futon Critic'',  March 29, 2005. Retrieved: March 8, 2008.</ref> The television premiere was on May 20, 2005 at 8:00pm on ABC in the US, where it was rated [[TV-PG]].<ref name=\"video\"/> It aired in Canada on [[CBC Television]], and in the UK on December 18, 2005. In the US, the film's official soundtrack was released on May 17, 2005.<ref name=\"ozcd\"/> [[Buena Vista Home Entertainment]] released the DVD and VHS in both the US and in international territories.<ref name=\"video\">[http://disneydvd.disney.go.com/the-muppets-wizard-of-oz.html#5161 \"''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz'' at Disney Videos.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201081157/http://disneydvd.disney.go.com/the-muppets-wizard-of-oz.html |date=2008-12-01 }}  [[Walt Disney Home Entertainment|Disney Videos]]. Retrieved: April 8, 2008.</ref> The film was released to [[DVD region code#1|Region 1]] [[DVD]] and [[VHS]] on August 9, 2005.<ref name=\"amazon\">[https://www.amazon.com/dp/B00005JO4H \"''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz'' DVD/VHS.\"]  [[Amazon.com]]. Retrieved: March 4, 2008.</ref> The Canadian Home Video Classification System rated the film [[G]] for all home video releases within Canadian territories.<ref name=\"kerry\"/> The [[DVD region code#2|Region 2]] DVD was released on April 3, 2006.<ref name=\"cinderella\">[https://www.amazon.co.uk/dp/B000CS47EK \"''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz'' Region 2 DVD.\"] [[Amazon.com]]. Retrieved: March 4, 2008.</ref> The film was rated U by the [[British Board of Film Classification]],<ref name=\"bbfc\">[http://www.bbfc.co.uk/website/Classified.nsf/0/763E06C9DBC036D98025711C0045B546?OpenDocument  \"''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz'' rated U by the BBFC.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081009141728/http://www.bbfc.co.uk/website/Classified.nsf/0/763E06C9DBC036D98025711C0045B546?OpenDocument |date=2008-10-09 }} [[BBFC]]. Retrieved: March 7, 2008.</ref> K-3 in [[Finland]],<ref name=finland>[http://195.197.150.133/elokuvahaku/EH1200.aspx?lcid=1035 \"''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz'' rated \"3\" by the FBFC (VET).\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080224195823/http://195.197.150.133/elokuvahaku/EH1200.aspx?lcid=1035 |date=2008-02-24 }} [[Finnish Board of Film Classification|VET]]. Retrieved: March 7, 2008.</ref> and G in Australia.<ref name=\"australia\">[http://www.ezydvd.com.au/item.zml/788247 \"''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz''&nbsp;\u2013 Anniversary Edition.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080314034116/http://www.ezydvd.com.au/item.zml/788247 |date=2008-03-14 }} [[EzyDVD]]. Retrieved: March 7, 2008.</ref> The DVD and VHS were released under the title ''[[Special edition|Extended Version]]'' in the US<ref name=\"amazon\"/> and ''[[Special edition|Anniversary Edition]]'' outside the US.<ref name=\"cinderella\"/> The extended version contains 20&nbsp;minutes of footage cut from the feature film,<ref name=\"julia\"/> including the footage of the [[Kelly Osbourne]] and [[Quentin Tarantino]] cameos.<ref name=\"julia\"/> The DVD and VHS included an extended interview with Quentin Tarantino, a blooper reel, and a behind-the-scenes look at the film guided by [[Pepe the Prawn]].<ref>[http://www.buy.com/prod/muppets-wizard-of-oz/q/loc/322/40718163.html \"DVD at Buy.com.\"] [[Buy.com]]. Retrieved: March 4, 2008.</ref> In the US, the DVD and VHS release of the film was in a 1.33:1 ([[Fullscreen (filmmaking)|fullscreen]]) aspect ratio, whereas the international versions are in the original 1.78:1 ([[widescreen]]) aspect ratio.<ref name=\"amazon\"/><ref name=\"australia\"/> During [[Macy's]] annual Flower Show promotion, the store's windows along [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]] displayed flower arrangements illustrating six scenes from the movie, while the store sold ''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz''-related merchandise, such as plush dolls.<ref>\"Muppet Wizardry at Macy''s.\" ''License'', Vol. 8, Issue 4, p. 11, May 2005. Retrieved: January 17, 2012.</ref>\n\n===Critical reception===\n7.75&nbsp;million viewers watched ''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz'' on its television premiere night in the United States; it ranked as the forty-second most-watched television program of the week.<ref name=\"viewing\">[http://www.abcmedianet.com/web/dnr/dispDNR.aspx?id=052405_04 \"Weekly Program Rankings.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090516042311/http://www.abcmedianet.com/web/dnr/dispDNR.aspx?id=052405_04 |date=2009-05-16 }} [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] Medianet, May 24, 2005. Retrieved: October 22, 2008.</ref> Michael Schneider of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' wrote that it \"performed solidly ... particularly with adults 18\u201334, teens and kids.\"<ref name=\"queenlatifah\">Schneider, Michael. [http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117931517.html?categoryid=1236&cs=1&s=h&p=0 \"The Muppets pull strings at ABC.\"] ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', October 24, 2005. Retrieved: April 5, 2008.</ref> The film received negative reviews from critics. At [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the movie currently holds a 38% rating, based on 8 reviews.<ref name=\"rottentomatoes\">[http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1147402-the_muppets_wizard_of_oz/ \"''The Muppets: Wizard of Oz'' at Rotten Tomatoes.\"] [[Rotten Tomatoes]]. Retrieved: November 23, 2008.</ref>\n\nFor the film's positive response, Kevin Carr stated that \"When you dig down and actually find (and watch) the new Muppet material, some of the magic is still there.\"<ref>Carr, Kevin. [http://www.7mpictures.com/inside/reviews/muppetswizarddvd_review.htm \"''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz'' Kevin Carr review.\"] 7Mpictures. Retrieved: March 5, 2008.</ref> [[MaryAnn Johanson]] of Flick Filosopher said that, \"It's not on a par with the Muppet movie madness of old, but it's darn close.\"<ref>Johanson, MaryAnn. [http://www.flickfilosopher.com/blog/2005/08/the_muppets_wizard_of_oz_revie.html \"''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz'' Maryann Johanson review.\"]  Flick Filosopher. Retrieved: March 4, 2008.</ref> According to the Bums Corner's review the film was a \"treat for all ages, and that it was a colorful, musical, humorous romp.\"<ref>[http://www.bumscorner.com/bumnuke/index.php?module=prodreviews&func=showcontent&id=104 \"Bums Corner review.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081005171256/http://www.bumscorner.com/bumnuke/index.php?module=prodreviews&func=showcontent&id=104 |date=2008-10-05 }} Bums Corner, May 21, 2005. Retrieved: March 4, 2008.</ref> Keith Allen of Movie Rapture gave the film 2.5 stars out of 3, explaining that the film's humor was surprisingly clever, and that the film would frequently make you laugh.<ref>Allen, Keith. [http://www.movierapture.com/muppetswizardofoz.htm \"''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz'' (2005).\"] Movie Rapture. Retrieved: March 4, 2008.</ref> [[Mutant Reviewers From Hell|Mutant Reviewers]] commented that although the Muppet deal with Walt Disney was \"disappointing\", the film managed to be funny and witty.<ref>[http://www.mutantreviewers.com/rmupwizard.html \"Mutant Reviewers from Hell do ''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz''.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080307201645/http://www.mutantreviewers.com/rmupwizard.html |date=2008-03-07 }} Mutant Reviewers. Retrieved: March 4, 2008.</ref>\n \nFor the film's negative response, David Nusair of Reel Film Reviews warned that the film was \"strictly for kids.\"<ref name=\"david\">Nusair, David. [http://www.reelfilm.com/dismupp.htm#wizard \"Five Muppet Movies from Disney.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080113063526/http://www.reelfilm.com/dismupp.htm |date=2008-01-13 }}  Reel Film Reviews. Retrieved: March 5, 2008.</ref> Nusair stated that although Ashanti can sing, she cannot act.<ref name=\"david\"/> Joshua Tyler of Cinema Blend explained that Dorothy visiting the Wizard of Oz to become a star instead of going back home was a big mistake,<ref name=\"misspiggy\">Tyler, Joshua. [http://www.cinemablend.com/dvds/The-Muppets-Wizard-of-Oz-1064.html \"''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz'' - DVD.\"] Cinema Blend, July 31, 2005. Retrieved: March 7, 2008.</ref> and that it showed how shallow society has become.<ref name=\"misspiggy\"/> R.J. Carter of The Trades gave the film a B-, also stating that Dorothy's wish to become a star was a selfish one.<ref>Carter, R.J. [http://www.the-trades.com/article.php?id=3434 \"DVD Review: ''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz''.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060523004538/http://www.the-trades.com/article.php?id=3434 |date=2006-05-23 }} The Trades, August 7, 2005. Retrieved: April 4, 2008.</ref> Ultimate Disney's review found that the extended version of the film did more harm than good;<ref name=\"julia\">[http://www.ultimatedisney.com/muppetsoz.html \"''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz'' Ultimate Disney DVD review.\"] ''[[Disney|Ultimate Disney]]'', August 9, 2005. Retrieved: April 26, 2008.</ref> Andy Dursin of The Aisle Seat said that the original film was \"dull\" and that the extended version was an improvement.<ref name=\"andy\">[http://www.andyfilm.com/8-10-05.html \"Kung Fu Craziness: Andy Reviews Stephen Chow's ''Kung Fu Hustle'' Plus: ''Winn-Dixie'' and ''The Muppets Visit Oz''!\"] The Aisle Seat, August 10, 2005. Retrieved: April 4, 2008.</ref> Cold Fusion Video felt that although the film was entertaining, it lacked the heart and wit of Jim Henson's Muppet films.<ref name=\"cold\">[http://www.coldfusionvideo.com/archives/muppets-wizard-of-oz-the-2005/ \"''Muppets\u2019 Wizard of Oz, The'' (2005).\"] Cold Fusion Video, August 31, 2005. Retrieved: April 4, 2008.</ref> Bryan Pope of DVD Verdict said that the film drained the Muppets of their spirit and was slightly gratuitous.<ref>[http://www.dvdverdict.com/reviews/muppetswizardoz.php \"Bryan Pope review.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080325062534/http://www.dvdverdict.com/reviews/muppetswizardoz.php |date=2008-03-25 }} DVD Verdict. Retrieved: April 4, 2008.</ref> Techtite TV reviews felt that the film was done poorly on all levels, and that the film was on the higher end of TV-PG.<ref>[http://www.techtite.com/Reviews/Tv/2005/Mupptwizoz.html \"''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz'': A Review by Techtite.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080513045309/http://www.techtite.com/Reviews/Tv/2005/Mupptwizoz.html |date=2008-05-13 }} Techtite TV Reviews. Retrieved: April 4, 2008.</ref>\n\nOther reviewers felt that the film's attempt to appeal to an older, more mature audience was ultimately a bad idea. Kerry Bennett of Parent Previews warned that it sometimes steered \"dangerously off course\" due to an excess of sexual content and violence.<ref name=\"kerry\">Bennett, Kerry. [http://www.parentpreviews.com/movie-reviews/muppets-wizard-of-oz.shtml \"''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz''.\"] Parent Previews. Retrieved: April 4, 2008.</ref> Referential humor to the marriage of [[Jennifer Lopez]], [[Manolo Blahnik]] style silver shoes, and films such as ''[[Girls Gone Wild (franchise)|Girls Gone Wild]]'', ''[[The Passion of the Christ]]'', ''[[Apocalypse Now]]'', and ''[[Kill Bill: Volume 1]]'' were seen as too mature.<ref name=\"david\"/><ref>Kelleher, Terry. \"The Muppets' Wizard Of Oz.\" ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'', Volume 63, Issue 20, May 23, 2005, p. 39.</ref> Cold Fusion Video judged the Kelly Osbourne cameo as \"pointless\".<ref name=\"cold\"/> Dursin contrasted the two guest appearances and found that the Tarantino cameo dragged the film down.<ref name=\"andy\"/> Critics were split on the merits of ABC's modernized adaptation to rely on plot elements from the [[The Wonderful Wizard of Oz|original novel]] instead of the iconic 1939 film.<ref name=\"comp\"/><ref>[http://www.moria.co.nz/fantasy/muppetswizardofoz.htm \"Richard Scheib film review.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080423052511/http://www.moria.co.nz/fantasy/muppetswizardofoz.htm |date=2008-04-23 }} Moria.co.nz, 2007. Retrieved: April 4, 2008.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n[[List of television films produced for American Broadcasting Company]]\n{{Clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://muppets.disney.com/the-muppets-wizard-of-oz}}\n*{{IMDb title|0422778}}\n*{{rotten-tomatoes|1147402-the_muppets_wizard_of_oz|The Muppets' Wizard of Oz}}\n*{{AllRovi movie|325674}}\n\n{{good article}}\n{{Muppet films}}\n{{Oz}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Muppets Wizard Of Oz}}\n[[Category:2005 television films]]\n[[Category:Canadian television films]]\n[[Category:Canadian films]]\n[[Category:The Muppets films]]\n[[Category:The Muppets television specials]]\n[[Category:The Jim Henson Company films]]\n[[Category:2000s children's fantasy films]]\n[[Category:American television films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American children's films]]\n[[Category:2005 soundtracks]]\n[[Category:Walt Disney Records soundtracks]]\n[[Category:Film soundtracks]]\n[[Category:Wizards in television]]\n[[Category:Films based on The Wizard of Oz]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Michael Giacchino]]\n[[Category:Canadian musical films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Kirk Thatcher]]\n[[Category:Films about witchcraft]]\n[[Category:Films set in Kansas]]\n[[Category:Television films by 20th Century Fox Television]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name = The Muppets'<br />Wizard of Oz\n| image = Woz-poster001sm.png\n| image_alt = \n| caption = Official poster\n| genre = <!--Must be sourced per Template:Infobox television instructions-->\n| based_on = ''[[The Wonderful Wizard of Oz]]'' by [[L. Frank Baum]]\n| writer = {{plainlist|\n* Debra Frank\n* Steve L. Hayes\n* Quentin Tarantino\n* [[Tom Martin (writer)|Tom Martin]]\n* [[Adam F. Goldberg]]\n}}\n| story = {{Plainlist|\n* Debra Frank\n* Steve L. Hayes\n}}\n| director = [[Kirk Thatcher]]\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Ashanti (singer)|Ashanti]]\n* [[Jeffrey Tambor]]\n* [[Quentin Tarantino]]\n* [[David Alan Grier]]\n* [[Queen Latifah]]\n* [[Steve Whitmire]]\n* [[Dave Goelz]]\n* [[Bill Barretta]]\n* [[Eric Jacobson]]\n}}\n| theme_music_composer = [[Michael Giacchino]]\n| country = {{Plainlist|\n* United States\n* Canada\n}}\n| language = English\n| producer = [[Bill Barretta]]\n| editor = Gregg Featherman\n| cinematography = Tony Westman\n| runtime = {{Plainlist|\n* 72 minutes\n* 100 minutes (Extended Edition)\n}}\n| company = {{Plainlist|\n* [[The Jim Henson Company]]\n* [[The Muppets Holding Company]]\n* [[ABC Studios|Touchstone Television]]\n* [[Fox 21 Television Studios|Fox Television Studios]]\n}}\n| distributor = [[Buena Vista Television]]\n| network = [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]\n| first_aired = {{Film date|2005|04|27|[[Tribeca Film Festival|Tribeca]]|2005|05|20|TV=y}}\n}}\n'''''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz''''' is a 2005 [[fantasy]] [[television film]] directed by [[Kirk Thatcher]] and starring [[Ashanti (singer)|Ashanti]] and [[The Muppets]] with supporting roles done by [[Jeffrey Tambor]], [[Quentin Tarantino]], [[David Alan Grier]], and [[Queen Latifah]]. The film was produced by [[Bill Barretta]] and written by Debra Frank, Steve L. Hayes, [[Tom Martin (writer)|Tom Martin]], and [[Adam F. Goldberg]] based on a story by Frank and Hayes.\n\nA modernized adaptation of [[L. Frank Baum]]'s 1900 novel, ''[[The Wonderful Wizard of Oz]]'', the story follows young [[Dorothy Gale]], who works in her Aunt Em's diner, but dreams of becoming a singer somewhere beyond her small Kansas town. Swept up by a tornado, in her [[trailer home]] with pet prawn Toto, she lands in Oz and embarks on a journey to meet the Wizard who can help make her dreams come true.\n\nThe film was co-produced by [[The Muppets Studio]], [[ABC Studios|Touchstone Television]], and [[Fox 21 Television Studios|Fox Television Studios]], in association with [[The Jim Henson Company]]. Right after Disney bought the rights to The Muppets in 2004, pre-production on ''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz'' took place throughout February 2004, and [[Principal photography|filming]] occurred during September 2004. ABC made several changes to the film after the initial script was written, ultimately deciding to adapt plot elements from Baum's original novel rather than the 1939 [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] musical film, ''[[The Wizard of Oz (1939 film)|The Wizard of Oz]]''. As with the preceding [[The Muppets|Muppet]] films, ''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz'' became a musical, and included five new songs written and composed by [[Michael Giacchino]]. The special is the first Muppets special without the involvement of veteran performer [[Jerry Nelson]] following his 2004 retirement from physical performing. His characters of [[List of Muppets#Lew Zealand|Lew Zealand]] and [[Dr. Teeth and the Electric Mayhem#Sgt. Floyd Pepper|Floyd Pepper]], were respectively performed by [[Bill Barretta]] and [[John Kennedy (puppeteer)|John Kennedy]]. Barretta also debuts as the new permanent performer of [[Dr. Teeth and The Electric Mayhem#Dr. Teeth|Dr. Teeth]] due to Kennedy now performing Floyd. The production also marked the feature film debut of [[Eric Jacobson]] as the performer of [[Sam Eagle]], a character originally performed by [[Frank Oz]].\n\n''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz'' premiered on April 27, 2005 at the [[Tribeca Film Festival]]. The film's television premiere was broadcast on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] on May 20, 2005, as the final ''[[ABC Movie of the Week]]''. The film received generally mixed to negative reviews from critics, who felt that the film was too mature for young audiences and that the cameo scenes and popular culture references were unnecessary.\n\n==Plot==\n{{plot|date=September 2018}}\n[[Dorothy Gale]] ([[Ashanti (singer)|Ashanti]]) is an orphaned teenage girl living in a trailer park in [[Kansas]]. Her [[Aunt Em]] ([[Queen Latifah]]) and [[Uncle Henry (Oz)|Uncle Henry]] ([[David Alan Grier]]) own a diner, to which Dorothy works for [[room and board]]. Her dream of becoming a singer is slim, but when waiting on some [[Truck driver|trucker]]s Dorothy overhears that the Muppets are conducting a cross-country show called \"Star Hunt\" and are looking for a backup singer. Aunt Em disapproves, but with Uncle Henry's best wishes, she goes to the audition. However, the Muppets are about to end the audition, and Dorothy only manages to give them a demo CD that she created beforehand. In returning home, the [[civil defense siren]]s sound as a [[tornado]] is headed for Dorothy's trailer park. When Aunt Em and Uncle Henry run into the county storm shelter for safety, Dorothy hurries back to her family's mobile home to get [[Toto (Oz)|Toto]], her pet [[prawn]]. She does not make it out in time, and the two are swept by the tornado across the vast fields of Kansas. When Dorothy climbs out of the wreckage, she finds that Toto ([[Pep\u00e9 the King Prawn]]) can talk and that she is no longer in Kansas.\n\nDorothy and Toto discover that they are in [[Munchkin Country|Munchkinland]], a small town part of the vast [[Land of Oz]]. After discussing her situation with the town's people, the Munchkins (played by [[Rizzo the Rat]] and the other rats), she learns that the land's ruler the [[Wizard of Oz (character)|Wizard]], has the power to grant her wish of becoming a famous singer. She meets the [[Good Witch of the North]] ([[Miss Piggy]]), and receives a pair of magic [[Silver Shoes|silver slippers]] from the [[Wicked Witch of the East]] (Miss Piggy), the Witch of the North's sister who was killed when Dorothy's trailer fell on her. Soon after, she embarks on a journey with Toto on the [[yellow brick road]] to meet the Wizard of Oz, who lives in the [[Emerald City]], the capital of Oz. On her journey, she meets three creatures: a [[Scarecrow (Oz)|Scarecrow]] ([[Kermit the Frog|Kermit]]), a [[Tin Woodman|Tin Thing]] ([[Gonzo (Muppet)|Gonzo]]), and a [[Cowardly Lion]] ([[Fozzie Bear|Fozzie]]). They are also seeking the Wizard of Oz to give them a brain, heart, and courage, respectively. The group meets various obstacles involving a deep gorge where the Kalidah Critics ([[Statler and Waldorf]]) are heckling them and a Poppy Field Club run by [[List of Muppets#Clifford|Clifford]] which nearly puts them to sleep. After arriving at the Emerald City and meeting the Wizard, Dorothy and her friends are sent to retrieve the [[Wicked Witch of the West]]'s magic eye, a tool she uses to see anything she desires in the Land of Oz.\n\nThe group assumes that completing this task will result in the granting of their wishes. The Wicked Witch of the West (Miss Piggy) sees them coming and consults with her pet [[List of Muppets#Additional characters|Foo-Foo]] and her henchman [[List of Muppets#Johnny Fiama and Sal Minella|Johnny Fiama]]. When the Wicked Witch of the West plans to have either her pack of 40 great man-eating wolves, a flock of 40 [[American crow|crow]]s of despair, a swarm of angry black bees, a group of vicious squirrels, or a group of bloodthirsty cockatoos to do away with them, Johnny tells her that the animals that work for her are unavailable due to various reasons. This forces her to resort to using her Magic Biker Cap to call Sal Minella and the other [[Winged monkeys|Flying Monkeys]] (played by [[List of Muppets#Sweetums|Sweetums]], [[List of Muppets#Crazy Harry|Crazy Harry]], Black Dog, Bobo the Bear, Calico, Old Tom, Spotted Dick, and Aretha from ''[[Fraggle Rock]]'') to deal with them. The Witch and the Flying Monkeys capture Dorothy, Toto and Lion while Scarecrow and Tin Thing are dismantled by the Flying Monkeys.\n\nAfter being threatened to be killed by her, Toto calls the Munchkins, who set him and Dorothy free and hold up the witch. During the final battle, it cuts away to a scene where [[Quentin Tarantino]] is having a meeting with Kermit, discussing ideas for how Dorothy can defeat the Wicked Witch of the West. Tarantino's ideas are deemed too expensive and too violent for a Muppet movie, so they agree for Dorothy to do a powerful kick on the witch. Cutting back to the action, Dorothy kicks the witch into her own \"bottled water bath\" which contains tap water (to which she is severely allergic). Angel Marie admitted that he filled the water bottles with tap water to restock them. This action causes the Wicked Witch of the West to melt as Johnny averts Foo-Foo's eyes. With the Wicked Witch of the West dead, Dorothy finds the magic eye floating in the tub unharmed and grabs it.\n\nDorothy gains control of the Flying Monkeys by giving back the group's Magic Biker Cap to Sal Minella. She has Scarecrow and Tin Thing rebuilt by the Flying Monkeys. Then she and her friends travel back to the Emerald City to have their wishes granted. When they all storm into the Wizard's room, they discover it is merely a Hollywood effects stage and that the Wizard ([[Jeffrey Tambor]]) is just an ordinary man, pretending. He asked for the witch's eye so that she could not see him for who he really was. Even so, he still proceeds to grant their wishes. Dorothy finally becomes a singer in the Land of Oz, but she realizes that all she ever really wanted was to go back home and be with her family. After traveling back to Munchkinland, she meets [[Glinda the Good Witch|Glinda the Good Witch of the South]] (Miss Piggy), who tells her that if she clicks her heels together three times, she will be able to go anywhere she desires, contrary to how the Good Witch of the North said to get to the Emerald City. She does so, saying \"take me home to Aunt Em\".\n\nShe is then spun by the slippers' charm into Kansas, and, much to her surprise, she finds out that Kermit was looking for her, saying that she had the best voice they heard on the whole search, and that she has been chosen to go on the Star Hunt. Dorothy, having been reunited with her aunt and uncle, and feeling that she is not ready to leave Kansas to become a real star, rejects, but Aunt Em says that she wants her to go with the Muppets on their Star Hunt, much to her even bigger surprise. She then sings \"Good Life\" on television with them at the Muppet Theater as the film ends.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Ashanti (singer)|Ashanti]] as [[Dorothy Gale]]: A [[Kansas]] teen dreaming of leaving her home and becoming a singer.\n* [[Queen Latifah]] as [[Aunt Em]]: Dorothy's aunt and co-owner of the family diner in Kansas.\n* [[David Alan Grier]] as [[Uncle Henry (Oz)|Uncle Henry]]: Dorothy's uncle and co-owner of the family diner.\n* [[Jeffrey Tambor]] as The [[Wizard of Oz (character)|Wizard of Oz]]: The legendary Wizard of Oz. This is Tambor's second appearance in a ''Muppet'' film, the first being ''[[Muppets from Space]]''.\n* [[Quentin Tarantino]] as Himself ''([[#Distribution|Extended version]])'': In a short appearance with [[Kermit the Frog]], Tarantino discusses violent ideas on how to stop the [[Wicked Witch of the West]]. Despite the fact that his role is minor, his name is still mentioned in the movie trailer and listed on the cover of both the Video and DVD.\n* [[Kelly Osbourne]] as [[Dorothy Gale]] (post-makeover) ''([[#Distribution|Extended version]])'': Appears in a brief cameo as Dorothy when she first comes out of the ''Magic Makeover Machine'' in [[Emerald City]].\n\n===Muppet performers===\n{{main|List of Muppets}}\n\n* [[Steve Whitmire]] as:\n** [[Kermit the Frog]] as Himself/[[Scarecrow (Oz)|Scarecrow]]: A scarecrow in search of a brain. Scarecrow is constantly mocked by the crows in Oz, as he is defenseless and cannot do anything to stop them. Prior to Dorothy's journey, Kermit organizes a talent scout for a star for a new show. After Dorothy's return, he hires her.\n** [[Beaker (Muppet)|Beaker]]: He appears as an Emerald City Technician. Beaker also appears at the end in the Muppets' show.\n** [[Rizzo the Rat]] as Himself/Mayor of Munchkinland. He occasionally aids Dorothy when she is in danger. Prior to Dorothy's journey, Rizzo is seen assisting [[Bean Bunny]] in loading equipment into the Muppets' bus. He returns for the Muppets' show at the end of the film.\n** [[Statler and Waldorf|Statler]] as Kalidah Critic #1. He heckles Dorothy and her friends as they try to cross a log.\n* [[Dave Goelz]] as:\n** [[Gonzo (Muppet)|The Great Gonzo]] as the Himself/[[Tin Woodman|Tin Thing]]: A robot in search of a heart. Originally human, the Tin Thing was turned into a robot by the Wicked Witch of the West who was angry at him for asking to leave her palace and marry his [[Engagement|fianc\u00e9e]], [[Camilla the Chicken]]. He also appears at the end of the film in the Muppets' show.\n** [[Bunsen Honeydew|Dr. Bunsen Honeydew]]: He appears as an Emerald City Technician. He also appears at the end of the film in the Muppets' show.\n** [[Statler and Waldorf|Waldorf]] as Kalidah Critic #2. He and the other Kalidah Critic heckles Dorothy and her friends as they try to cross a log.\n** [[Dr. Teeth and The Electric Mayhem#Zoot|Zoot]]: He performs backup for the songs \"Naptime\", and for \"The Witch is in the House\", and appears at the end of the film in the Muppets' new show.\n* [[Bill Barretta]] as:\n** [[Pep\u00e9 the King Prawn]] as [[Toto (Oz)|Toto]]: Dorothy's pet prawn and first companion on her journey. In Kansas, Toto was a prawn that lived in a fish bowl in Dorothy's room. Strangely, Pep\u00e9 doesn't appear in the finale with the other Muppets.\n** [[Dr. Teeth and The Electric Mayhem#Dr. Teeth|Dr. Teeth]]: He performs \"Naptime\", and also performs in \"The Witch is in the House\". He appears again at the end of the film in the Muppets' show.\n** [[List of Muppets#Johnny Fiama and Sal Minella|Johnny Fiama]]: He appears as one of the henchmen of the Wicked Witch of the West, and is supposedly her love interest. \n** [[List of Muppets#Lew Zealand|Lew Zealand]]: He briefly appears in Emerald City at the red carpet event, asking Dorothy to sign his boomerang fish. \n** [[Swedish Chef|The Swedish Chef]]: He provides the [[Bran Flakes]] for the Wizard. \n** Bubba the Rat: He assists the Mayor of Munchkin Land in getting Dorothy and the Lion out of Poppyfields.\n* [[Eric Jacobson]] as:\n** [[Miss Piggy]] as Herself: She appears early on with Kermit, and tries to get rid of Dorothy. She returns at the end of the film for the Muppets' show.\n*** as The [[Wicked Witch of the West]]: The Wicked Witch that terrifies all that meet her.\n*** as The [[Good Witch of the North|Tattypoo the Good Witch of the North]]: The Good Witch that gives Dorothy the silver slippers.\n*** as The [[Glinda the Good Witch|Glinda the Good Witch of the South]]: The other Good Witch that shows Dorothy how to get home.\n*** as The [[Wicked Witch of the East]]: The original owner of the magic slippers who was killed by Dorothy's falling mobile home.\n** [[Fozzie Bear]] as Himself/[[Cowardly Lion|Cowardly Bear]]: A nervous and frightened lion stand-up comic that accompanies Dorothy and the others on their journey. Fozzie shows up at the end of the film in the Muppets' show.\n** [[Animal (Muppet)|Animal]]: He performs in the songs \"Naptime\" and \"The Witch is in the House\".\n** [[Sam Eagle]]: He appears as the Guardian of the Gates. Sam doesn't appear in the Muppets' show at the end of the film.\n* [[Brian Henson]] as:\n** Sal Manilla as Sal, a [[Winged monkeys|Flying Monkey]]: He accompanies Johnny for much of the film.\n* [[Kevin Clash]] as:\n** [[List of Muppets#Clifford|Clifford]]: He appears as the manager of the Poppy Field Club. \n** Mulch: He appears briefly in Poppyfields.\n** Black Dog as a [[Winged monkeys|Flying Monkey]]\n* [[John Kennedy (puppeteer)|John Kennedy]] as:\n** Angel Marie as a [[Winged monkeys|Flying Monkey]]: A servant of the Wicked Witch of the West.\n** [[Dr. Teeth and The Electric Mayhem#Sgt. Floyd Pepper|Floyd Pepper]]: He performs in \"Naptime\" and \"The Witch is in the House\".\n* Rickey Boyd as:\n** [[Scooter (Muppet)|Scooter]]: He appears as the Wizard's Assistant.\n** [[List of Muppets#Crazy Harry|Crazy Harry]] as a [[Winged monkeys|Flying Monkey]]\n* [[Tyler Bunch]] as:\n** [[Dr. Teeth and The Electric Mayhem#Janice|Janice]]: She performs in \"Naptime\" and \"The Witch is in the House\".\n** Old Tom as a [[Winged monkeys|Flying Monkey]]\n* [[Julianne Buescher]] as\n** Wizard's Green Lady and Chicken Forms\n* [[John Henson (puppeteer)|John Henson]] as\n** [[List of Muppets#Sweetums|Sweetums]] as a [[Winged monkeys|Flying Monkey]]: He provides the keys for the Cowardly Lion's escape from his cage.\n* [[Mike Quinn (puppeteer)|Mike Quinn]] as\n** Spotted Dick as a [[Winged monkeys|Flying Monkey]]\n* [[Allan Trautman]] as\n** [[American crow|Crow]]: He bothers the Scarecrow.\n** Old Tom as a [[Winged monkeys|Flying Monkey]]\n* [[Alice Dinnean]] as:\n** [[List of Muppets#Camilla the Chicken|Camilla the Chicken]]: The Tin Thing's girlfriend. The two are reunited later on in the film.\n** [[List of Muppets#Additional characters|Foo-Foo]]: Foo-Foo appears as the pet of the Wicked Witch of the West.\n\nWhitmire and Goelz make on-screen cameos as audience members at Aunt Em's Diner during the finale.\n\n==Production==\nWhen [[The Walt Disney Company]] acquired the Muppets franchise from [[The Jim Henson Company]] in February 2004,<ref name=\"llc\">[http://www.henson.com/muppets.php \"''The Muppets'' at the Jim Henson Company.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080510143755/http://www.henson.com/muppets.php |date=2008-05-10 }} [[The Jim Henson Company]]. Retrieved: April 26, 2008.</ref><ref name=\"fozzie\">[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/3603954.stm \"Tarantino to star in Muppets film,\"] ''[[BBC News]]'', August 27, 2004, Retrieved: April 26, 2008.</ref> the Muppets were re-introduced to the public by marketing products and guest appearing on television shows such as ''[[Good Morning America]]'' and ''[[America's Funniest Home Videos]]''.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}} After a new film titled ''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz'' was announced by [[The Jim Henson Company]], [[Fox 21 Television Studios|Fox Television Studios]], [[Touchstone Television]], and the [[The Muppets Studio|Muppets Holding Company]] signed on to help produce it.<ref name=\"oz\">Gates, Anita. [https://www.nytimes.com/2005/05/20/arts/television/20mupp.html \"Muppets as Munchkins: We're Not in Kansas Anymore.\"] ''[[The New York Times]]'', May 20, 2005, p. E26. Retrieved: March 11, 2008.</ref>\n\nFilming took place throughout September 2004 in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]].<ref name=\"fozzie\"/> Before filming, ABC announced that the production would adapt elements from the original 1900 book, rather than [[The Wizard of Oz (1939 film)|the 1939 film]].<ref name=\"comp\">Adalian, Josef. [http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117901774.html?categoryid=1236&cs=1&query=muppets+oz \"The Muppets ready to take Oz.\"] ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', March 15, 2004. Retrieved: April 26, 2008.</ref> such as the [[Silver Shoes]] instead of the [[Ruby slippers]].  On August 25, 2004, it was announced that [[Hilary Duff]], [[Jessica Simpson]], and [[Ashanti (entertainer)|Ashanti]] had auditioned for the role of [[Dorothy Gale]], but Ashanti had won the part.<ref>Norment, Lynn. [http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1077/is_5_60/ai_n12934945 \"Ashanti: Answers critics & doubters.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120601021517/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1077/is_5_60/ai_n12934945/ |date=2012-06-01 }} ''[[Ebony (magazine)|Ebony]]'', March 2005. Retrieved: April 26, 2008.</ref><ref>[http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1490550/20040825/ashanti.jhtml \"For The Record: Quick News On Ashanti, Usher, Phil Spector, Taking Back Sunday, Kanye West, Jay-Z & More.\"] ''[[MTV]]'', August 25, 2004. Retrieved: April 26, 2008.</ref> When asked about how she felt about working with the Muppets, Ashanti replied, \"I love children, and to me, the Muppets are just like little kids.\"<ref name=\"gonzo\">Fonseca, Nicholas. [http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,1060837,00.html \"Wizard of Frog.\"] ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'', Issue 820, p. 66, May 20, 2005. Retrieved: April 26, 2008.</ref> She also stated, \"The director had to give me a few pointers and tips for acting with them, but the most important thing that I learned was to keep eye contact.\"<ref name=\"gonzo\"/> Also in August 2004, [[BBC News]] reported that [[Quentin Tarantino]] would appear in the film.<ref name=\"fozzie\"/>\n\n==Music==\n[[Michael Giacchino]], who had previously worked on a Muppet-related project which is video game ''[[Muppet Monster Adventure]]'' and would become an [[Academy Award]]-winning composer, worked with Jeannie Lurie, Adam Cohen, Debra Frank, and Steve Hayes to write five original songs for the film.<ref name=\"fozzie\"/><ref name=\"a\"/> The five songs created were \"Kansas\", \"When I'm With You\", \"It's a Good Life\", \"The Witch is in the House\", and \"Nap Time\". \"When I'm With You\" was later nominated for a [[Primetime Emmy]] in the Outstanding Music and Lyrics category,<ref name=\"emmy\">[http://www.emmys.tv/awards/2005pt/awards/music.php \"''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz'' nominated for Primetime Emmy.\"] [[Emmy Awards]]. Retrieved: March 27, 2008.</ref> but lost to \"Mary Jane/Mary Lane\" from ''[[Reefer Madness (2005 film)|Reefer Madness]]''.<ref name=\"emmy\"/> Ashanti and the Muppet cast, mainly Bill Barretta and Eric Jacobson, contributed the vocals for each of the songs.<ref name=\"a\"/> Ted Kryczko produced the album, Booker T. Washington White prepared the songs for recording, and Paul Silveira and Brandon Christy mixed the film's songs.<ref name=\"a\"/>\n\n===Soundtrack===\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Best of the Muppets featuring The Muppets' Wizard of Oz\n| type       = Soundtrack\n| artist     =\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = May 17, 2005\n| recorded   = [[Walt Disney Studios (Burbank)|Walt Disney Studios]]\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Pop rock]], [[soundtrack]]<ref name=\"ozcd\"/>\n| length     = 29:52<ref name=\"a\">''The Best of the Muppets featuring The Muppets' Wizard of Oz''. [[Walt Disney Records]], 2005.</ref>\n| label      = [[Walt Disney Records|Walt Disney]]\n| producer   = [[Sam Pottle]]\n| chronology = [[The Muppets]]\n| prev_title = [[The Muppet Show: Music, Mayhem, and More]]\n| prev_year  = 2002\n| next_title = [[The Muppets: A Green and Red Christmas]]\n| next_year  = 2006\n}}\n''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz'' official soundtrack was released on May 17, 2005.<ref name=\"ozcd\">[https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0009AJK98 \"''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz'' Soundtrack.\"] ''[[Amazon.com]]'', 2005. Retrieved: March 4, 2008.</ref> The album was an enhanced soundtrack titled ''Best of Muppets featuring The Muppets' Wizard of Oz'' as it was not a film-specific soundtrack, but an album featuring the Muppets' best songs from ''[[The Muppet Show]]'' as well as songs from the film.<ref name=\"ozcd\"/>\n\n'''Track listing'''<ref name=\"ozcd\"/>\n# \"''(Gotta Get Outta)''<ref>''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz DVD Film Intro, [[Closed Captioning]]''. ''[[Walt Disney Home Video]]'', 2005. Retrieved: April 26, 2008.</ref> Kansas\" - [[Ashanti (entertainer)|Ashanti]]\n# \"When I'm With You\" \u2013 [[Ashanti (entertainer)|Ashanti]], Kermit, Gonzo, Fozzie & Pepe\n# \"The Witch Is in the House\" \u2013 [[Miss Piggy]] with [[Dr. Teeth and The Electric Mayhem]]\n# \"Calling All Munchkins\" \u2013 The Munchkin Tap-Your-Knuckles Choir\n# \"Good Life\" \u2013 [[Ashanti (entertainer)|Ashanti]]\n# \"Nap Time\" \u2013 [[Dr. Teeth and The Electric Mayhem]]\n# \"[[The Muppet Show Theme]]\" \u2013 The Muppets\n# \"[[Mah N\u00e0 Mah N\u00e0]]\"\u2013 [[Mah N\u00e0 Mah N\u00e0|Mahna Mahna]] & the Two Snowths\n# \"[[Bein' Green]]\"\u2013 [[Kermit the Frog]]\n# \"[[Rainbow Connection]]\" \u2013 Kermit & Muppets With Sesame Street Gang \n# \"Lady of Spain\" \u2013 [[Marvin Suggs]] & his Muppaphone\n# \"[[Halfway Down the Stairs]]\"\u2013 Kermit & [[Robin the Frog|Robin]]\n# \"[[What Now My Love?]]\" \u2013 [[Miss Piggy]]\n# \"Tenderly\" \u2013 [[Dr. Teeth and The Electric Mayhem]]\n# \"Happy Feet\" \u2013 Kermit and the Frog Chorus\n\n==Release==\n''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz'' premiered on April 27, 2005 at the [[Tribeca Film Festival]].<ref>[http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news.aspx?id=20050329muppets01 \"''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz'' to premiere on April 27th, 2005 at the Tribeca Film Festival.\"] ''The Futon Critic'',  March 29, 2005. Retrieved: March 8, 2008.</ref> The television premiere was on May 20, 2005 at 8:00pm on ABC in the US, where it was rated [[TV-PG]].<ref name=\"video\"/> It aired in Canada on [[CBC Television]], and in the UK on December 18, 2005. In the US, the film's official soundtrack was released on May 17, 2005.<ref name=\"ozcd\"/> [[Buena Vista Home Entertainment]] released the DVD and VHS in both the US and in international territories.<ref name=\"video\">[http://disneydvd.disney.go.com/the-muppets-wizard-of-oz.html#5161 \"''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz'' at Disney Videos.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201081157/http://disneydvd.disney.go.com/the-muppets-wizard-of-oz.html |date=2008-12-01 }}  [[Walt Disney Home Entertainment|Disney Videos]]. Retrieved: April 8, 2008.</ref> The film was released to [[DVD region code#1|Region 1]] [[DVD]] and [[VHS]] on August 9, 2005.<ref name=\"amazon\">[https://www.amazon.com/dp/B00005JO4H \"''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz'' DVD/VHS.\"]  [[Amazon.com]]. Retrieved: March 4, 2008.</ref> The Canadian Home Video Classification System rated the film [[G]] for all home video releases within Canadian territories.<ref name=\"kerry\"/> The [[DVD region code#2|Region 2]] DVD was released on April 3, 2006.<ref name=\"cinderella\">[https://www.amazon.co.uk/dp/B000CS47EK \"''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz'' Region 2 DVD.\"] [[Amazon.com]]. Retrieved: March 4, 2008.</ref> The film was rated U by the [[British Board of Film Classification]],<ref name=\"bbfc\">[http://www.bbfc.co.uk/website/Classified.nsf/0/763E06C9DBC036D98025711C0045B546?OpenDocument  \"''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz'' rated U by the BBFC.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081009141728/http://www.bbfc.co.uk/website/Classified.nsf/0/763E06C9DBC036D98025711C0045B546?OpenDocument |date=2008-10-09 }} [[BBFC]]. Retrieved: March 7, 2008.</ref> K-3 in [[Finland]],<ref name=finland>[http://195.197.150.133/elokuvahaku/EH1200.aspx?lcid=1035 \"''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz'' rated \"3\" by the FBFC (VET).\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080224195823/http://195.197.150.133/elokuvahaku/EH1200.aspx?lcid=1035 |date=2008-02-24 }} [[Finnish Board of Film Classification|VET]]. Retrieved: March 7, 2008.</ref> and G in Australia.<ref name=\"australia\">[http://www.ezydvd.com.au/item.zml/788247 \"''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz''&nbsp;\u2013 Anniversary Edition.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080314034116/http://www.ezydvd.com.au/item.zml/788247 |date=2008-03-14 }} [[EzyDVD]]. Retrieved: March 7, 2008.</ref> The DVD and VHS were released under the title ''[[Special edition|Extended Version]]'' in the US<ref name=\"amazon\"/> and ''[[Special edition|Anniversary Edition]]'' outside the US.<ref name=\"cinderella\"/> The extended version contains 20&nbsp;minutes of footage cut from the feature film,<ref name=\"julia\"/> including the footage of the [[Kelly Osbourne]] and [[Quentin Tarantino]] cameos.<ref name=\"julia\"/> The DVD and VHS included an extended interview with Quentin Tarantino, a blooper reel, and a behind-the-scenes look at the film guided by [[Pepe the Prawn]].<ref>[http://www.buy.com/prod/muppets-wizard-of-oz/q/loc/322/40718163.html \"DVD at Buy.com.\"] [[Buy.com]]. Retrieved: March 4, 2008.</ref> In the US, the DVD and VHS release of the film was in a 1.33:1 ([[Fullscreen (filmmaking)|fullscreen]]) aspect ratio, whereas the international versions are in the original 1.78:1 ([[widescreen]]) aspect ratio.<ref name=\"amazon\"/><ref name=\"australia\"/> During [[Macy's]] annual Flower Show promotion, the store's windows along [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]] displayed flower arrangements illustrating six scenes from the movie, while the store sold ''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz''-related merchandise, such as plush dolls.<ref>\"Muppet Wizardry at Macy''s.\" ''License'', Vol. 8, Issue 4, p. 11, May 2005. Retrieved: January 17, 2012.</ref>\n\n===Critical reception===\n7.75&nbsp;million viewers watched ''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz'' on its television premiere night in the United States; it ranked as the forty-second most-watched television program of the week.<ref name=\"viewing\">[http://www.abcmedianet.com/web/dnr/dispDNR.aspx?id=052405_04 \"Weekly Program Rankings.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090516042311/http://www.abcmedianet.com/web/dnr/dispDNR.aspx?id=052405_04 |date=2009-05-16 }} [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] Medianet, May 24, 2005. Retrieved: October 22, 2008.</ref> Michael Schneider of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' wrote that it \"performed solidly ... particularly with adults 18\u201334, teens and kids.\"<ref name=\"queenlatifah\">Schneider, Michael. [http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117931517.html?categoryid=1236&cs=1&s=h&p=0 \"The Muppets pull strings at ABC.\"] ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', October 24, 2005. Retrieved: April 5, 2008.</ref> The film received negative reviews from critics. At [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the movie currently holds a 38% rating, based on 8 reviews.<ref name=\"rottentomatoes\">[http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1147402-the_muppets_wizard_of_oz/ \"''The Muppets: Wizard of Oz'' at Rotten Tomatoes.\"] [[Rotten Tomatoes]]. Retrieved: November 23, 2008.</ref>\n\nFor the film's positive response, Kevin Carr stated that \"When you dig down and actually find (and watch) the new Muppet material, some of the magic is still there.\"<ref>Carr, Kevin. [http://www.7mpictures.com/inside/reviews/muppetswizarddvd_review.htm \"''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz'' Kevin Carr review.\"] 7Mpictures. Retrieved: March 5, 2008.</ref> [[MaryAnn Johanson]] of Flick Filosopher said that, \"It's not on a par with the Muppet movie madness of old, but it's darn close.\"<ref>Johanson, MaryAnn. [http://www.flickfilosopher.com/blog/2005/08/the_muppets_wizard_of_oz_revie.html \"''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz'' Maryann Johanson review.\"]  Flick Filosopher. Retrieved: March 4, 2008.</ref> According to the Bums Corner's review the film was a \"treat for all ages, and that it was a colorful, musical, humorous romp.\"<ref>[http://www.bumscorner.com/bumnuke/index.php?module=prodreviews&func=showcontent&id=104 \"Bums Corner review.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081005171256/http://www.bumscorner.com/bumnuke/index.php?module=prodreviews&func=showcontent&id=104 |date=2008-10-05 }} Bums Corner, May 21, 2005. Retrieved: March 4, 2008.</ref> Keith Allen of Movie Rapture gave the film 2.5 stars out of 3, explaining that the film's humor was surprisingly clever, and that the film would frequently make you laugh.<ref>Allen, Keith. [http://www.movierapture.com/muppetswizardofoz.htm \"''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz'' (2005).\"] Movie Rapture. Retrieved: March 4, 2008.</ref> [[Mutant Reviewers From Hell|Mutant Reviewers]] commented that although the Muppet deal with Walt Disney was \"disappointing\", the film managed to be funny and witty.<ref>[http://www.mutantreviewers.com/rmupwizard.html \"Mutant Reviewers from Hell do ''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz''.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080307201645/http://www.mutantreviewers.com/rmupwizard.html |date=2008-03-07 }} Mutant Reviewers. Retrieved: March 4, 2008.</ref>\n \nFor the film's negative response, David Nusair of Reel Film Reviews warned that the film was \"strictly for kids.\"<ref name=\"david\">Nusair, David. [http://www.reelfilm.com/dismupp.htm#wizard \"Five Muppet Movies from Disney.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080113063526/http://www.reelfilm.com/dismupp.htm |date=2008-01-13 }}  Reel Film Reviews. Retrieved: March 5, 2008.</ref> Nusair stated that although Ashanti can sing, she cannot act.<ref name=\"david\"/> Joshua Tyler of Cinema Blend explained that Dorothy visiting the Wizard of Oz to become a star instead of going back home was a big mistake,<ref name=\"misspiggy\">Tyler, Joshua. [http://www.cinemablend.com/dvds/The-Muppets-Wizard-of-Oz-1064.html \"''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz'' - DVD.\"] Cinema Blend, July 31, 2005. Retrieved: March 7, 2008.</ref> and that it showed how shallow society has become.<ref name=\"misspiggy\"/> R.J. Carter of The Trades gave the film a B-, also stating that Dorothy's wish to become a star was a selfish one.<ref>Carter, R.J. [http://www.the-trades.com/article.php?id=3434 \"DVD Review: ''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz''.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060523004538/http://www.the-trades.com/article.php?id=3434 |date=2006-05-23 }} The Trades, August 7, 2005. Retrieved: April 4, 2008.</ref> Ultimate Disney's review found that the extended version of the film did more harm than good;<ref name=\"julia\">[http://www.ultimatedisney.com/muppetsoz.html \"''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz'' Ultimate Disney DVD review.\"] ''[[Disney|Ultimate Disney]]'', August 9, 2005. Retrieved: April 26, 2008.</ref> Andy Dursin of The Aisle Seat said that the original film was \"dull\" and that the extended version was an improvement.<ref name=\"andy\">[http://www.andyfilm.com/8-10-05.html \"Kung Fu Craziness: Andy Reviews Stephen Chow's ''Kung Fu Hustle'' Plus: ''Winn-Dixie'' and ''The Muppets Visit Oz''!\"] The Aisle Seat, August 10, 2005. Retrieved: April 4, 2008.</ref> Cold Fusion Video felt that although the film was entertaining, it lacked the heart and wit of Jim Henson's Muppet films.<ref name=\"cold\">[http://www.coldfusionvideo.com/archives/muppets-wizard-of-oz-the-2005/ \"''Muppets\u2019 Wizard of Oz, The'' (2005).\"] Cold Fusion Video, August 31, 2005. Retrieved: April 4, 2008.</ref> Bryan Pope of DVD Verdict said that the film drained the Muppets of their spirit and was slightly gratuitous.<ref>[http://www.dvdverdict.com/reviews/muppetswizardoz.php \"Bryan Pope review.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080325062534/http://www.dvdverdict.com/reviews/muppetswizardoz.php |date=2008-03-25 }} DVD Verdict. Retrieved: April 4, 2008.</ref> Techtite TV reviews felt that the film was done poorly on all levels, and that the film was on the higher end of TV-PG.<ref>[http://www.techtite.com/Reviews/Tv/2005/Mupptwizoz.html \"''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz'': A Review by Techtite.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080513045309/http://www.techtite.com/Reviews/Tv/2005/Mupptwizoz.html |date=2008-05-13 }} Techtite TV Reviews. Retrieved: April 4, 2008.</ref>\n\nOther reviewers felt that the film's attempt to appeal to an older, more mature audience was ultimately a bad idea. Kerry Bennett of Parent Previews warned that it sometimes steered \"dangerously off course\" due to an excess of sexual content and violence.<ref name=\"kerry\">Bennett, Kerry. [http://www.parentpreviews.com/movie-reviews/muppets-wizard-of-oz.shtml \"''The Muppets' Wizard of Oz''.\"] Parent Previews. Retrieved: April 4, 2008.</ref> Referential humor to the marriage of [[Jennifer Lopez]], [[Manolo Blahnik]] style silver shoes, and films such as ''[[Girls Gone Wild (franchise)|Girls Gone Wild]]'', ''[[The Passion of the Christ]]'', ''[[Apocalypse Now]]'', and ''[[Kill Bill: Volume 1]]'' were seen as too mature.<ref name=\"david\"/><ref>Kelleher, Terry. \"The Muppets' Wizard Of Oz.\" ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'', Volume 63, Issue 20, May 23, 2005, p. 39.</ref> Cold Fusion Video judged the Kelly Osbourne cameo as \"pointless\".<ref name=\"cold\"/> Dursin contrasted the two guest appearances and found that the Tarantino cameo dragged the film down.<ref name=\"andy\"/> Critics were split on the merits of ABC's modernized adaptation to rely on plot elements from the [[The Wonderful Wizard of Oz|original novel]] instead of the iconic 1939 film.<ref name=\"comp\"/><ref>[http://www.moria.co.nz/fantasy/muppetswizardofoz.htm \"Richard Scheib film review.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080423052511/http://www.moria.co.nz/fantasy/muppetswizardofoz.htm |date=2008-04-23 }} Moria.co.nz, 2007. Retrieved: April 4, 2008.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n[[List of television films produced for American Broadcasting Company]]\n{{Clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://muppets.disney.com/the-muppets-wizard-of-oz}}\n*{{IMDb title|0422778}}\n*{{rotten-tomatoes|1147402-the_muppets_wizard_of_oz|The Muppets' Wizard of Oz}}\n*{{AllRovi movie|325674}}\n\n{{good article}}\n{{Muppet films}}\n{{Oz}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Muppets Wizard Of Oz}}\n[[Category:2005 television films]]\n[[Category:Canadian television films]]\n[[Category:Canadian films]]\n[[Category:The Muppets films]]\n[[Category:The Muppets television specials]]\n[[Category:The Jim Henson Company films]]\n[[Category:2000s children's fantasy films]]\n[[Category:American television films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American children's films]]\n[[Category:2005 soundtracks]]\n[[Category:Walt Disney Records soundtracks]]\n[[Category:Film soundtracks]]\n[[Category:Wizards in television]]\n[[Category:Films based on The Wizard of Oz]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Michael Giacchino]]\n[[Category:Canadian musical films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Kirk Thatcher]]\n[[Category:Films about witchcraft]]\n[[Category:Films set in Kansas]]\n[[Category:Television films by 20th Century Fox Television]]\n", "name_user": "50.104.16.23", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eMuppet performers)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Muppets%27_Wizard_of_Oz"}
{"title_page": "William Smith (physician)", "text_new": "[[File:Dr. William Smith an early Osteopath physician and associate of Andrew Still.png|thumb|Dr. William Smith an early Osteopath physician and associate of Andrew Still]]\n'''William Smith''' (1862-1912) was a [[Scottish]] American physician who was an early proponent of [[osteopathic medicine]] and an early associate of [[Andrew Still]] in Missouri.\n\nWilliam Smith was born in 1862 [[Jamaica]] while his Scottish father was working as an engineer on the island.  Smith grew up in Scotland attended medical school in [[Edinburgh]]. He practiced medicine in Europe before attempting to start a practice in Brooklyn, New York.  After finding limited success in New York, he then traveled west and met Andrew Still in Missouri in June 1892.  After investigating Still's claims, Smith agreed to serve as the first anatomy professor at Still's new school, which was opening in September, and Smith helped in the founding of several other osteopathic institutions. In 1893 Smith received the first doctor of osteopathy degree from Still's school. Smith briefly served as president of the [[Atlantic School of Osteopathy]] in Pennsylvania. In 1912 he returned to Scotland after several unsuccessful attempts at starting a practice in the United States.  He died of pneumnoia in [[Dundee, Scotland]] in 1912.<ref>E. R. N. GRIGG, \"Peripatetic Pioneer: William Smith, M.D., D.O. (1862-1912),\" ''Journal of the History of Medicine and Allied Sciences,'' Vol. 22, No. 2 (April, 1967), pp. 169-179 accessed on [[JSTOR]]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1862 births]]\n[[Category:1912 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century American physicians]]\n[[Category:19th-century American scientists]]\n[[Category:American osteopathic physicians|.]]\n[[Category:American osteopaths]]\n[[Category:Osteopaths]]\n[[Category:Scottish physicians]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Dr. William Smith an early Osteopath physician and associate of Andrew Still.png|thumb|Dr. William Smith an early Osteopath physician and associate of Andrew Still]]\n'''William Smith''' (1862-1912) was a [[Scottish]] American physician who was an early proponent of [[osteopathic medicine]] and an early associate of [[Andrew Still]] in Missouri.\n\nWilliam Smith was born in 1862 [[Jamaica]] while his Scottish father was working as an engineer on the island.  Smith grew up in Scotland attended medical school in [[Edinburgh]]. He practiced medicine in Europe before attempting to start a practice in Brooklyn, New York.  After finding limited success in New York, he then traveled west and met Andrew Still in Missouri in June of 1892.  After investigating Still's claims, Smith agreed to serve as the first anatomy professor at Still's new school, which was opening in September, and Smith helped in the founding of several other osteopathic institutions. In 1893 Smith received the first doctor of osteopathy degree from Still's school. Smith briefly served as president of the [[Atlantic School of Osteopathy]] in Pennsylvania. In 1912 he returned to Scotland after several unsucessful attempts at starting a practice in the United States.  He died of pneumnoia in [[Dundee, Scotland]] in 1912. <ref>E. R. N. GRIGG, \"Peripatetic Pioneer: William Smith, M.D., D.O. (1862-1912),\" ''Journal of the History of Medicine and Allied Sciences,'' Vol. 22, No. 2 (April, 1967), pp. 169-179 accessed on [[JSTOR]]</ref>\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n[[Category:1862 births]]\n[[Category:1912 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century American physicians]]\n[[Category:19th-century American scientists]]\n[[Category:American osteopathic physicians|.]]\n[[Category:American osteopaths]]\n[[Category:Osteopaths]]\n[[Category:Scottish physicians]]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: unsucessful \u2192 unsuccessful", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Smith_(physician)"}
{"title_page": "1968 Macdonald Brier", "text_new": "{{infobox curling\n| Name = 1968 Macdonald Brier\n| Logo = \n| Size = \n| Host city = [[Kelowna, British Columbia]]<ref name=\"MontGaz4\">{{cite news |title=Ontario rated Brier dark horse |date=1968-03-04 |page=24 |newspaper=The Montreal Gazette |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1946&dat=19680304&id=G4IuAAAAIBAJ&sjid=AqAFAAAAIBAJ&pg=4116,565151&hl=en |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n| Arena = [[Kelowna Arena]]<ref name=\"soudog1968pdf\">{{cite news|title=BRIER BY THE NUMBERS |date=1969-02-10 |page=8 |url=http://soudogcurling.tripod.com/Brier/BrierRecords.pdf |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n| Dates =  March 4\u20138<ref>{{cite news|title=1968 MacDonald Brier - Scores |url=https://www.curlingzone.com/event.php?eventid=63&view=Scores&showdrawid=1#1 |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n| Attendance = 25,813<ref name=\"soudog1968\">{{cite news|title=1968 MacDonald Brier |url=http://soudogcurling.tripod.com/Brier/1968.htm |accessdate=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n| Winner = '''{{AB}}'''\n| Curling club = [[Calgary Curling Club|Calgary CC]], [[Calgary]]\n| Skip = [[Ron Northcott]]\n| Third = [[Jim Shields]]\n| Second = [[Bernie Sparkes]]\n| Lead = [[Fred Storey]]\n| Finalist =  {{SK}}\n|Curling club2 = [[Avonlea Curling Club]] ([[Avonlea, Saskatchewan]])\n|Skip2 = [[Bob Pickering]]\n|Third2 = [[Jack Keys (curler)|Jack Keys]]\n|Second2 = [[Garnet Campbell]]\n|Lead2 = [[Gary Ford]]\n|Alternate2 = \n|Coach2 = \n|Finalist2 = \n| prev = [[1967 Macdonald Brier|1967]]\n| next = [[1969 Macdonald Brier|1969]]\n}}\n\nThe '''1968 [[Macdonald Brier]]''', Canada's national men's [[curling]] championship was held March 4&ndash;8 at the [[Kelowna Arena]] in [[Avonlea, Saskatchewan]].\n\nThe Ron Northcott rink representing Alberta won their second title with an impressive 9\u20131 record. It was also the 10th title for Alberta.\n\nSaskatchewan were runners-up, with 8\u20132 record. Prince Edward Island were at the third place at 7-3 records.<r