web/20120405155719/http://www.allnightrva.com/ AllNightRVA.com]  \n* [http://www.astoldoverbrunch.com/ As Told Over Brunch]\n* Carver & Jackson Ward News [http://cjwn.net]\n* Church Hill People's News [http://www.chpn.net]\n* community.livejournal.com/rva [[LiveJournal]]\n* [http://DowntownShortPump.com DowntownShortPump.com] \n* Fan District Hub [https://web.archive.org/web/20070930081607/http://fdhub.net/]\n* Hills and Heights [http://hillsandheights.net]\n* Near West End News [http://nearwestendnews.net]\n* North Richmond News [http://northrichmondnews.com]\n* OurHealthRichmond.com [http://ourhealthrichmond.com]\n* Punchline Magazine comedy site, now defunct underground culture newspaper  [http://punchlinemagazine.com]\n* Richmond City Watch [http://www.richmondcitywatch.com]\n* [[Richmond.com]] (''[[Richmond Times-Dispatch]]'') \n* richmond.craigslist.org [[Craigslist]]\n* richmond.indymedia.org [[indymedia]]\n* [http://www.richmondbizsense.com RichmondBizSense.com] \n* [http://RichmondGrid.com RichmondGrid.com] \n* www.richmondliberty.org\n* River City Rapids [http://rivercityrapids.com]\n* RVA Magazine (http://Rvamag.com)\n* RVANews.com [http://rvanews.com]\n* RVAPlaylist.com [http://www.rvaplaylist.com]\n* South Richmond News [https://web.archive.org/web/20171003192252/http://www.southsiderichmond.com/]\n* Spyed (https://web.archive.org/web/20120621012644/http://spyedrichmond.com/)\n* TalkRVA.com [http://www.talkrva.com]\n* Virginia Christmas News [https://web.archive.org/web/20101208232449/http://virginiachristmasnews.com/]\n* West of the Boulevard News [http://wotbn.net]\n\n==Media corporations ==\nCommercial radio ownership in Richmond is dominated by three companies:\n \n* [[Entercom]]  (WRVA-AM, WRVQ, WTVR-FM, WBTJ, WRXL, WRNL-AM)\n* [[SummitMedia LLC]]  (WKLR, WMXB, WJSR, WKHK)\n* [[Urban One]]  (WCDX, WKJS, WKJX, WPZZ, WTPS-AM)\n\n[[Commonwealth Public Broadcasting Corporation]] is the owner of several stations in Richmond (WCVE-TV, WCVE-FM, WWLB-FM, WBBT-FM, WCVW-TV), along with translators in [[Charlottesville]], and another station in [[Northern Virginia]], and is headquartered in Richmond.\n\n==Communication schools==\nRichmond is home to the [http://masscomm.vcu.edu/ VCU School of Mass Communications], which was founded in 1978 and offers bachelor's and master's degrees in journalism, advertising and public relations. It  is accredited by the Accrediting Council on Education in Journalism and Mass Communication (AEJMC). The school houses [http://capitalnews.vcu.edu/ Capital News Service], [https://web.archive.org/web/20140112220621/http://insight.vcu.edu/ VCU InSight], and the [http://createathononcampus.org/about/ VCU Create-A-thon].\n\n==See also==\n* [[Virginia#Media|Virginia media]]\n** [[List of newspapers in Virginia]]\n** [[List of radio stations in Virginia]]\n** [[List of television stations in Virginia]]\n** Media of [[List of cities in Virginia|cities]] in Virginia: [[Chesapeake, Virginia#Media|Chesapeake]], [[Hampton, Virginia#Media|Hampton]], [[Newport News, Virginia#Media|Newport News]], [[Norfolk, Virginia#Media|Norfolk]], [[Roanoke, Virginia#Media|Roanoke]], [[Virginia Beach, Virginia#Media|Virginia Beach]]\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.richmondmedia.com/ Richmond Media - a Richmond media company specializing in web design and broadband video]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071008104355/http://www.mediaweek.com/mw/search/article_display.jsp?schema=&vnu_content_id=1001010621 2005 ''Mediaweek'' review of Richmond-Petersburg Media]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060517010320/http://www.nielsenmedia.com/DMAs.html www.nielsenmedia.com DMA rankings]\n* {{cite web |url= http://dmoztools.net/Regional/North_America/United_States/Virginia/Localities/R/Richmond/News_and_Media/ |work=[[DMOZ]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |title= United States: Virginia: Richmond: News and Media }} (Directory ceased in 2017)\n\n{{Richmond, Virginia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Media In Richmond, Virginia}}\n[[Category:Media in Richmond, Virginia|*]]\n[[Category:Lists of media by city in the United States|Richmond]]\n", "text_old": "{{Unr|date=March 2017}}\nAccording to [http://www.nielsen.com/content/dam/corporate/us/en/docs/solutions/measurement/television/2015-2016-dma-ranks.pdf nielsenmedia.com] statistics for 2015\u20132016, the [[Richmond-Petersburg|Richmond, Virginia]] market area is the 56th largest [[Designated Market Area]] in the United States, with 549,730 TV households. Richmond is served by a variety of communication [[Mass media|media]]:\n\n==Print media==\n\n===Daily===\nThe local daily [[newspaper]] in Richmond is the ''[[Richmond Times-Dispatch]]''.\n\n===Weekly===\n*''Brick'' (defunct alternative weekly; published September 2006 to July 2010)\n*''Style Weekly'' ([[alternative weekly]])\n*''Chesterfield Observer''\n\n===Monthly / bi-monthly / quarterly ===\n*''Boomer Magazine'' (bi-monthly)\n*''Chesterfield Living'', ''West Ends Best'', ''Hanover Lifestyle'' (bi-monthly)\n*''Greater Richmond Grid Magazine''  (bi-monthly)\n*''OurHealth Richmond Magazine'' (bi-monthly)\n*''[[Richmond Magazine]]'' (monthly)\n*''[[RVA Magazine]]''[http://www.rvamag.com] (quarterly)\n*''Whurk'' (monthly)\n\n====News and newsmagazines====\n{{see also|List of newspapers in Virginia }}\nThe ''[[Richmond Free Press]]''[http://www.richmondfreepress.com/] and the ''[[Richmond Voice]]'' [http://www.voicenewspaper.com] are weekly newspapers that cover the news from a predominantly [[African American]] perspective. The only Hispanic magazine in the state, ''[[La Voz Hispana de Virginia]]'' [http://www.lavozhispana.us] provides significant cultural and news content in both English and Spanish.  There are also two major publications from the Jewish community of Richmond, published in English; ''The Reflector'' is the semi-weekly newspaper of the [[Jewish Federation]] of Richmond and ''Virginia Jewish Life'' (formerly ''Virginia Jewish News'') is an independent monthly magazine published by the [[Chabad]] community of Richmond, but highlighting stories of general Jewish interest in Virginia.  ''City Edition'' was a civic-minded newspaper that listed municipal and council related events, issues, and results, which stopped publication in October 2007. [http://www.thecommunityweekly.com/]. ''[http://www.richmond.com/ Richmond.com]'' is an online newsmagazine with a wide readership. Other local topical publications include ''Richmond Parents Magazine'' and ''[http://www.myvmagazine.com V Magazine for Women]''. the voice of women in Richmond. [http://www.myvmagazine.com] ''[[Richmond Guide]]'' [http://www.richmondguide.com] is a quarterly that is targeted toward visitors. ''[[The Virginia Defender]]'' [http://defendersfje.org/id3.html] is a quarterly statewide community newspaper with a press run of 16,000 distributed through nearly 300 distribution sites in Richmond, plus 16 other Virginia cities and five counties.\n\n[[File:Richmond Planet Sat May 31 1902.jpg|thumb|Richmond Planet on Saturday May 31, 1902.]]\nRichmond's leading African American newspaper at the turn of the century was the ''[[Richmond Planet]]'' which ran from 1883-1996 and was edited by [[John Mitchel, Jr.]] from 1884 until his death in 1929.\n\nRegional and county newspapers include the following: \n* ''[[The Amelia Bulletin Monitor]]'' for [[Amelia County, Virginia]] [http://www.ameliamonitor.com/]\n* The ''Chesterfield Observer'' for [[Chesterfield County, Virginia]] [https://web.archive.org/web/20060106073630/http://www.richmond.com/partners/chesterfieldobserver.aspx]\n* The ''Goochland Courier'' for [[Goochland County, Virginia]]\n* The ''Goochland Gazette'' for [[Goochland County, Virginia]] [http://www.goochlandgazette.com/]\n* The ''Henrico Citizen'' for [[Henrico County, Virginia]] [https://archive.today/20051106032517/http://www.richmond.com/partners/henricocitizen.aspx]\n* The ''Herald Progress'' for [[Hanover County, Virginia]] [https://archive.today/20051128050710/http://www.richmond.com/partners/heraldprogress.aspx]\n* ''The Hopewell News'' (defunct) for [[Hopewell, Virginia]] [https://web.archive.org/web/20160207100701/http://www.hopewellnews.com/]\n* ''Petersburg Progress-Index'' for [[Petersburg, Virginia]][http://www.progress-index.com]\n* ''[[RVA Magazine]]'' [http://rvamag.com]\n* ''[[Virginia Living]]'' [http://www.virginialiving.com/] is a glossy magazine published bi-monthly that covers Virginia events.\n\n===Student ===\nVCU, VUU, and University of Richmond have student-run newspapers, including VCU's ''[[The Commonwealth Times|Commonwealth Times]]'', ''[http://inkmagazine.tumblr.com/ Ink]'', ''Amendment'', ''Emanata'', and ''[[Poictesme]]''.\n\n==Television ==\nRichmond is served by several television stations.\n\n===Broadcast===\nRichmond's over-the-air television stations:\n{| cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"1\" border=\"1\"\n|+ align=bottom |\n!style=\"background:#ffcccc;\"| '''Digital'''\n!style=\"background:#ffcccc;\"| '''Repack'''\n!style=\"background:#ffcccc;\"| '''PSIP'''\n!style=\"background:#ffcccc;\"| '''[[Callsign]]'''\n!style=\"background:#ffcccc;\"| '''Licensed To'''\n!style=\"background:#ffcccc;\"| '''Primary<br>Network(s)<br>[on HD1 Channel]'''\n!style=\"background:#ffcccc;\"| '''Digital<br>Subchannel(s)'''\n!style=\"background:#ffcccc;\"| '''Ownership'''\n!style=\"background:#ffcccc;\"| '''Website'''\n|-\n|  25 || 23 || 6 ||[[WTVR-TV|WTVR]] ||Richmond||[[CBS]]|| 6.2 - [[Antenna TV]]<br>6.3 - Xtra News ||[[E. W. Scripps Company]]|| http://www.wtvr.com\n|-\n| 22 || 28 || 8 || [[WRIC-TV|WRIC]]||Petersburg ||[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] ||8.2 - [[Ion Television]]<br>8.3 - [[GetTV]]<br>8.4 - [[Laff (TV network)|Laff]] ||[[Nexstar Media Group|Nexstar]] || http://www.wric.com\n|-\n| 12 || 10 || 12 || [[WWBT]]|| Richmond || [[NBC]] ||12.2 - [[Me-TV]]<br>12.3 - [[Circle (TV network)|Circle]]<br>12.4 - [[Court TV Mystery]] || [[Gray Television]] || http://www.nbc12.com\n|-\n| 15 || 15 || 15 || [[WUDW-LD|WUDW]] || Richmond 