ghtrva.com/ AllNightRVA.com]  \n* [http://www.astoldoverbrunch.com/ As Told Over Brunch]\n* Carver & Jackson Ward News [http://cjwn.net]\n* Church Hill People's News [http://www.chpn.net]\n* community.livejournal.com/rva [[LiveJournal]]\n* [http://DowntownShortPump.com DowntownShortPump.com] \n* Fan District Hub [https://web.archive.org/web/20070930081607/http://fdhub.net/]\n* Hills and Heights [http://hillsandheights.net]\n* Near West End News [http://nearwestendnews.net]\n* North Richmond News [http://northrichmondnews.com]\n* OurHealthRichmond.com [http://ourhealthrichmond.com]\n* Punchline Magazine comedy site, now defunct underground culture newspaper  [http://punchlinemagazine.com]\n* Richmond City Watch [http://www.richmondcitywatch.com]\n* [[Richmond.com]] (''[[Richmond Times-Dispatch]]'') \n* richmond.craigslist.org [[Craigslist]]\n* richmond.indymedia.org [[indymedia]]\n* [http://www.richmondbizsense.com RichmondBizSense.com] \n* [http://RichmondGrid.com RichmondGrid.com] \n* www.richmondliberty.org\n* River City Rapids [http://rivercityrapids.com]\n* RVA Magazine (http://Rvamag.com)\n* RVANews.com [http://rvanews.com]\n* RVAPlaylist.com [http://www.rvaplaylist.com]\n* South Richmond News [https://web.archive.org/web/20171003192252/http://www.southsiderichmond.com/]\n* Spyed (https://web.archive.org/web/20120621012644/http://spyedrichmond.com/)\n* TalkRVA.com [http://www.talkrva.com]\n* Virginia Christmas News [https://web.archive.org/web/20101208232449/http://virginiachristmasnews.com/]\n* West of the Boulevard News [http://wotbn.net]\n\n==Media corporations ==\nCommercial radio ownership in Richmond is dominated by three companies:\n \n* [[Entercom]]  (WRVA-AM, WRVQ, WTVR-FM, WBTJ, WRXL, WRNL-AM)\n* [[SummitMedia LLC]]  (WKLR, WMXB, WJSR, WKHK)\n* [[Urban One]]  (WCDX, WKJS, WKJX, WPZZ, WTPS-AM)\n\n[[Commonwealth Public Broadcasting Corporation]] is the owner of several stations in Richmond (WCVE-TV, WCVE-FM, WWLB-FM, WBBT-FM, WCVW-TV), along with translators in [[Charlottesville]], and another station in [[Northern Virginia]], and is headquartered in Richmond.\n\n==Communication schools==\nRichmond is home to the [http://masscomm.vcu.edu/ VCU School of Mass Communications], which was founded in 1978 and offers bachelor's and master's degrees in journalism, advertising and public relations. It  is accredited by the Accrediting Council on Education in Journalism and Mass Communication (AEJMC). The school houses [http://capitalnews.vcu.edu/ Capital News Service], [https://web.archive.org/web/20140112220621/http://insight.vcu.edu/ VCU InSight], and the [http://createathononcampus.org/about/ VCU Create-A-thon].\n\n==See also==\n* [[Virginia#Media|Virginia media]]\n** [[List of newspapers in Virginia]]\n** [[List of radio stations in Virginia]]\n** [[List of television stations in Virginia]]\n** Media of [[List of cities in Virginia|cities]] in Virginia: [[Chesapeake, Virginia#Media|Chesapeake]], [[Hampton, Virginia#Media|Hampton]], [[Newport News, Virginia#Media|Newport News]], [[Norfolk, Virginia#Media|Norfolk]], [[Roanoke, Virginia#Media|Roanoke]], [[Virginia Beach, Virginia#Media|Virginia Beach]]\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.richmondmedia.com/ Richmond Media - a Richmond media company specializing in web design and broadband video]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071008104355/http://www.mediaweek.com/mw/search/article_display.jsp?schema=&vnu_content_id=1001010621 2005 ''Mediaweek'' review of Richmond-Petersburg Media]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060517010320/http://www.nielsenmedia.com/DMAs.html www.nielsenmedia.com DMA rankings]\n* {{cite web |url= http://dmoztools.net/Regional/North_America/United_States/Virginia/Localities/R/Richmond/News_and_Media/ |work=[[DMOZ]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |title= United States: Virginia: Richmond: News and Media }} (Directory ceased in 2017)\n\n{{Richmond, Virginia}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Media In Richmond, Virginia}}\n[[Category:Media in Richmond, Virginia|*]]\n[[Category:Lists of media by city in the United States|Richmond]]\n", "name_user": "Time1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBroadcast", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Media_in_Richmond,_Virginia"}
{"title_page": "Blood in My Eye", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Blood in My Eye\n| type       = [[Album]]\n| artist     = [[Ja Rule]]\n| cover      = Ja Rule - Blood In My Eye album cover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = November 4, [[2003 in music|2003]]\n| recorded   = 2002-2003\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[East Coast hip hop]], [[gangsta rap]], [[hardcore hip hop]]\n| length     = 44:56\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Murder Inc Records|Murder Inc.]]|[[Def Jam Recordings|Def Jam]]}}\n| producer   = [[Irv Gotti]]\n| prev_title = [[The Last Temptation (Ja Rule album)|The Last Temptation]]\n| prev_year  = 2002\n| next_title = [[R.U.L.E.]]\n| next_year  = 2004\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Blood in My Eye\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Clap Back]]\n | single1date = October 14, 2003\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Blood in My Eye''''' is the fifth [[studio album]] by American [[rapper]] [[Ja Rule]]; it released on November 4, 2003, by [[Murder Inc Records|Murder Inc. Records]] and [[Def Jam Recordings]]. The album was originally planned to be released as a mixtape. The release of the album took place during the feud with [[Shady Records|Shady]]/[[Aftermath Records|Aftermath]] rappers [[50 Cent]], [[G-Unit]], [[Eminem]], [[D12]], [[Dr. Dre]], [[Obie Trice]], along with artists including [[DMX (rapper)|DMX]] and [[Busta Rhymes]] and was entirely dedicated to dissing them. The album was named after [[George Jackson (Black Panther)|George Jackson]]'s radical book of the same name.\n\n[[Hussein Fatal|Hussein Fatal of Outlawz]], [[Caddillac Tah (rapper)|Cadillac Tah]], James Gotti, [[Sizzla]], [[Black Child]], Young Merc, D.O. Cannon, Shadow, and Sekou 720 are listed as [[guest appearance]]s on this album. ''Blood in My Eye'' debuted at number 6 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart, with first-week sales of 139,000 copies in the United States.<ref>{{cite news|last=D'Angelo |first=Joe |url=http://www.cmt.com/news/country-music/1493813/eminem-shreds-the-competition-even-with-a-premature-encore.jhtml |title=Eminem Shreds The Competition, Even With A Premature Encore |work=[[CMT (U.S. TV channel)|CMT]] |date=November 17, 2004 |accessdate=January 16, 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Critical reception ==\n{{Album ratings\n| MC = 45/100<ref name=\"Metacritic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/blood-in-my-eye|title=Reviews for Blood In My Eye by Ja Rule|website=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=March 25, 2012}}</ref>\n|rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n|rev1score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref name=\"AM\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=mw0000320863|pure_url=yes}}|title=Blood in My Eye - Ja Rule|last=Birchmeier|first=Jason|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=July 10, 2011}}</ref>\n|rev2 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n|rev2score = C<ref name=\"EW\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,543142,00.html|title=Blood in My Eye Review|last=Endelman|first=Michael|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time Inc.]]|date=November 21, 2003|accessdate=March 25, 2012}}</ref>\n|rev3 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n|rev3score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2003/nov/07/popandrock.shopping6|title=CD: Ja Rule: Blood in My Eye|last=Lindon|first=Beccy|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]|date=November 7, 2003|accessdate=January 25, 2017|location=London}}</ref>\n|rev4 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n|rev4score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref name=\"RS\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/jarule/albums/album/300848/review/6068045/blood_in_my_eye |title=Ja Rule: Blood In My Eye |last=Caramanica |first=Jon |authorlink=Jon Caramanica |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |publisher=[[Jann Wenner|Wenner Media]] |date=November 19, 2003 |accessdate=September 30, 2007 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071016074814/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/jarule/albums/album/300848/review/6068045/blood_in_my_eye |archivedate=October 16, 2007 }}</ref>\n|rev5 = ''RapReviews''\n|rev5score = 5.5/10<ref name=\"RR\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rapreviews.com/archive/2003_11F_bloodin.html|title=Feature for November 4, 2003 - Ja Rule's \"Blood in My Eye\"|last=Juon|first=Steve 'Flash'|website=RapReviews|date=November 4, 2003|accessdate=July 10, 2011}}</ref>\n}}\n''Blood in My Eye'' garnered mixed reviews from [[Music journalism|music critic]]s, skeptical of Ja's lyrical skills as a hardcore rapper. At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[Standard score|normalized]] rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream critics, the album received an [[Weighted mean|average]] score of 45, based on 8 reviews.<ref name=\"Metacritic\"/>\n\nBeccy Lindon of ''[[The Guardian]]'' called the record \"a rough, back-to-basics rap album\", noting that it is filled with guest verses from hardcore rappers and devoid of R&B artists, concluding that it is \"more concerned with answering critics and continuing the backbiting with the [[Death Row Records|Death Row]] camp.\"<ref name=\"Guardian\"/> [[Jon Caramanica]], writing for ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', commended Ja for breaking away from his usual love duet formula to deliver shots at other rappers but said that \"the boasts here feel utterly tired. And so does the attitude.\"<ref name=\"RS\"/> Michael Endelman of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' found the album to be \"a dull slog with a dearth of hooks and a surfeit of gangsta clich\u00e9s.\"<ref name=\"EW\"/>\n\nSteve 'Flash' Juon of ''RapReviews'' criticized the narrow-minded lyrical takedowns and suggested that Ja sticks to mainstream R&B/hip-hop duets, despite crediting the production and collaborations with Hussein Fatal, saying that, \"All things considered though, this short 45 minute album will not solve Ja's problems, nor will it restore him to chart dominance.\"<ref name=\"RR\"/> [[AllMusic]] editor Jason Birchmeier called it \"a very focused and heartfelt album\", much more than his debut ''[[Venni Vetti Vecci]]'', but felt that Ja worked better as a mainstream rapper crafting \"catchy pop-rap tracks with grimy posturing and singalong hooks.\" He added that listeners would not get much out of the record, saying \"there are only two quality songs, a lot of redundant trash-talking, and an overall sense of ridiculousness that pervades.\"<ref name=\"AM\"/>\n\n== Track listing ==\n{{tracklist\n| extra_column    = Producer(s)\n| title1          = Murder Intro\n| note1           = \n| extra1          = Ja Rule, [[Irv Gotti]]\n| length1         = 0:26\n| title2          = The Life\n| note2           = featuring Hussein Fatal, [[Caddillac Tah (rapper)|Caddillac Tah]] & James Gotti\n| extra2          = Jimi Kendrix, Irv Gotti\n| length2         = 4:35\n| title3          = [[Clap Back]]\n| note3           = \n| extra3          = [[Scott Storch]], Irv Gotti\n| length3         = 4:57\n| title4          = The Crown\n| note4           = featuring [[Sizzla]]\n| extra4          = Irv Gotti, [[Chink Santana]]\n| length4         = 3:45\n| title5          = Kay Slay (Skit)\n| note5           = \n| extra5          = Ja Rule, Irv Gotti\n| length5         = 0:18\n| title6          = Things Gon' Change / 2 Punk Ass Quarters (Skit)\n| note6           = featuring [[Black Child (rapper)|Black Child]], Young Merc & D.O. Cannon\n| extra6          = Jimi Kendrix, Irv Gotti\n| length6         = 4:01\n| title7          = Race Against Time II\n| note7           = \n| extra7          = Jimi Kendrix, Irv Gotti\n| length7         = 3:53\n| title8          = Bobby Creep (Skit)\n| note8           = \n| extra8          = Irv Gotti, Rebel\n| length8         = 0:44\n| title9          = Niggas & Bitches\n| note9           = \n| extra9          = Irv Gotti, Blackout Movement\n| length9         = 4:34\n| title10         = The INC Is Back\n| note10          = featuring Shadow, Sekou 720 & [[Black Child (rapper)|Black Child]]\n| extra10         = Sekou 720, [[Swizz Beatz]]\n| length10        = 5:22\n| title11         = Remo (Skit)\n| note11          = \n| extra11         = Irv Gotti, Rebel\n| length11        = 1:13\n| title12         = Blood In My Eye\n| note12          = featuring Hussein Fatal\n| extra12         = Jimi Kendrix, Irv Gotti\n| length12        = 2:25\n| title13         = It's Murda Freestyle\n| note13          = featuring Hussein Fatal\n| extra13         = Irv Gotti\n| length13        = 3:36\n| title14         = The Wrap Freestyle\n| note14          = featuring Hussein Fatal\n| extra14         = Irv Gotti, Hussein Fatal\n| length14        = 5:09\n}}\n\n== Charts ==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (2003)\n!align=\"left\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{album chart|Australia|79|artist=Ja Rule|album=Blood in My Eye}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Germany|98|artist=Ja Rule|album=Blood in My Eye}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Switzerland|92|artist=Ja Rule|album=Blood in My Eye}}\n|-\n{{album chart|UK|51|artist=Ja Rule}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Billboard200|6|artist=Ja Rule|artistid=276599|accessdate=May 7, 2015}}\n|-\n{{album chart|BillboardRandBHipHop|1|artist=Ja Rule|artistid=276599|accessdate=May 7, 2015}}\n|-\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (2004)\n!Position\n|-\n| US Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums (''Billboard'')<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/2004/top-r-b-hip-hop-albums|title=Year-End Charts: R&B/Hip-Hop Albums - 2004|magazine=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|accessdate=May 7, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150719031416/http://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/2004/top-r-b-hip-hop-albums|archivedate=July 19, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|100\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Billboard number-one R&B albums of 2003]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Ja Rule}}\n\n[[Category:2003 albums]]\n[[Category:Ja Rule albums]]\n[[Category:Def Jam Recordings albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Scott Storch]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Irv Gotti]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Blood in My Eye\n| type       = [[Album]]\n| artist     = [[Ja Rule]]\n| cover      = Ja Rule - Blood In My Eye album cover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = November 4, [[2003 in music|2003]]\n| recorded   = 2002-2003\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[East Coast hip hop]], [[gangsta rap]], [[hardcore hip hop]]\n| length     = 44:56\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Murder Inc Records|Murder Inc.]]|[[Def Jam Recordings|Def Jam]]}}\n| producer   = [[Irv Gotti]]\n| prev_title = [[The Last Temptation (Ja Rule album)|The Last Temptation]]\n| prev_year  = 2002\n| next_title = [[R.U.L.E.]]\n| next_year  = 2004\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Blood in My Eye\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Clap Back]]\n | single1date = October 14, 2003\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Blood in My Eye''''' is the fifth [[studio album]] by American [[rapper]] [[Ja Rule]]; it released on November 4, 2003, by [[Murder Inc Records|Murder Inc. Records]] and [[Def Jam Recordings]]. The album was originally planned to be released as a mixtape. The release of the album took place during the feud with [[Shady Records|Shady]]/[[Aftermath Records|Aftermath]] rappers [[50 Cent]], [[G-Unit]], [[Eminem]], [[D12]], [[Dr. Dre]], [[Obie Trice]], along with artists including [[DMX (rapper)|DMX]] and [[Busta Rhymes]] and was entirely dedicated to dissing them. The album was named after [[George Jackson (Black Panther)|George Jackson]]'s radical book of the same name.\n\n[[Hussein Fatal|Hussein Fatal of Outlawz]], [[Caddillac Tah (rapper)|Cadillac Tah]], James Gotti, [[Sizzla]], [[Black Child]], Young Merc, D.O. Cannon, Shadow, and Sekou 720 are listed as [[guest appearance]]s on this album. ''Blood in My Eye'' debuted at number 6 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart, with first-week sales of 139,000 copies in the United States.<ref>{{cite news|last=D'Angelo |first=Joe |url=http://www.cmt.com/news/country-music/1493813/eminem-shreds-the-competition-even-with-a-premature-encore.jhtml |title=Eminem Shreds The Competition, Even With A Premature Encore |work=[[CMT (U.S. TV channel)|CMT]] |date=November 17, 2004 |accessdate=January 16, 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Critical reception ==\n{{Album ratings\n| MC = 45/100<ref name=\"Metacritic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/blood-in-my-eye|title=Reviews for Blood In My Eye by Ja Rule|website=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=March 25, 2012}}</ref>\n|rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n|rev1score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref name=\"AM\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=mw0000320863|pure_url=yes}}|title=Blood in My Eye - Ja Rule|last=Birchmeier|first=Jason|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=July 10, 2011}}</ref>\n|rev2 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n|rev2score = C<ref name=\"EW\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,543142,00.html|title=Blood in My Eye Review|last=Endelman|first=Michael|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time Inc.]]|date=November 21, 2003|accessdate=March 25, 2012}}</ref>\n|rev3 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n|rev3score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2003/nov/07/popandrock.shopping6|title=CD: Ja Rule: Blood in My Eye|last=Lindon|first=Beccy|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]|date=November 7, 2003|accessdate=January 25, 2017|location=London}}</ref>\n|rev4 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n|rev4score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref name=\"RS\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/jarule/albums/album/300848/review/6068045/blood_in_my_eye |title=Ja Rule: Blood In My Eye |last=Caramanica |first=Jon |authorlink=Jon Caramanica |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |publisher=[[Jann Wenner|Wenner Media]] |date=November 19, 2003 |accessdate=September 30, 2007 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071016074814/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/jarule/albums/album/300848/review/6068045/blood_in_my_eye |archivedate=October 16, 2007 }}</ref>\n|rev5 = ''RapReviews''\n|rev5score = 5.5/10<ref name=\"RR\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rapreviews.com/archive/2003_11F_bloodin.html|title=Feature for November 4, 2003 - Ja Rule's \"Blood in My Eye\"|last=Juon|first=Steve 'Flash'|website=RapReviews|date=November 4, 2003|accessdate=July 10, 2011}}</ref>\n}}\n''Blood in My Eye'' garnered mixed reviews from [[Music journalism|music critic]]s, skeptical of Ja's lyrical skills as a hardcore rapper. At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[Standard score|normalized]] rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream critics, the album received an [[Weighted mean|average]] score of 45, based on 8 reviews.<ref name=\"Metacritic\"/>\n\nBeccy Lindon of ''[[The Guardian]]'' called the record \"a rough, back-to-basics rap album\", noting that it is filled with guest verses from hardcore rappers and devoid of R&B artists, concluding that it is \"more concerned with answering critics and continuing the backbiting with the [[Death Row Records|Death Row]] camp.\"<ref name=\"Guardian\"/> [[Jon Caramanica]], writing for ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', commended Ja for breaking away from his usual love duet formula to deliver shots at other rappers but said that \"the boasts here feel utterly tired. And so does the attitude.\"<ref name=\"RS\"/> Michael Endelman of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' found the album to be \"a dull slog with a dearth of hooks and a surfeit of gangsta clich\u00e9s.\"<ref name=\"EW\"/>\n\nSteve 'Flash' Juon of ''RapReviews'' criticized the narrow-minded lyrical takedowns and suggested that Ja sticks to mainstream R&B/hip-hop duets, despite crediting the production and collaborations with Hussein Fatal, saying that, \"All things considered though, this short 45 minute album will not solve Ja's problems, nor will it restore him to chart dominance.\"<ref name=\"RR\"/> [[AllMusic]] editor Jason Birchmeier called it \"a very focused and heartfelt album\", much more than his debut ''[[Venni Vetti Vecci]]'', but felt that Ja worked better as a mainstream rapper crafting \"catchy pop-rap tracks with grimy posturing and singalong hooks.\" He added that listeners would not get much out of the record, saying \"there are only two quality songs, a lot of redundant trash-talking, and an overall sense of ridiculousness that pervades.\"<ref name=\"AM\"/>\n\n== Track listing ==\n{{tracklist\n| extra_column    = Producer(s)\n| title1          = Murder Intro\n| note1           = \n| extra1          = Ja Rule, [[Irv Gotti]]\n| length1         = 0:26\n| title2          = The Life\n| note2           = featuring Hussein Fatal, [[Caddillac Tah (rapper)|Caddillac Tah]] & James Gotti\n| extra2          = Jimi Kendrix, Irv Gotti\n| length2         = 4:35\n| title3          = [[Clap Back]]\n| note3           = \n| extra3          = [[Scott Storch]], Irv Gotti\n| length3         = 4:57\n| title4          = The Crown\n| note4           = featuring [[Sizzla]]\n| extra4          = Irv Gotti, [[Chink Santana]]\n| length4         = 3:45\n| title5          = Kay Slay (Skit)\n| note5           = \n| extra5          = Ja Rule, Irv Gotti\n| length5         = 0:18\n| title6          = Things Gon' Change / 2 Punk Ass Quarters (Skit)\n| note6           = featuring [[Black Child (rapper)|Black Child]], Young Merc & D.O. Cannon\n| extra6          = Jimi Kendrix, Irv Gotti\n| length6         = 4:01\n| title7          = Race Against Time II\n| note7           = \n| extra7          = Jimi Kendrix, Irv Gotti\n| length7         = 3:53\n| title8          = Bobby Creep (Skit)\n| note8           = \n| extra8          = Irv Gotti, Rebel\n| length8         = 0:44\n| title9          = Niggas & Bitches\n| note9           = \n| extra9          = Irv Gotti, Blackout Movement\n| length9         = 4:34\n| title10         = The INC Is Back\n| note10          = featuring Shadow, Sekou 720 & [[Black Child (rapper)|Black Child]]